What's the idea between packing these arguments into an array and then unpacking them inside the function rather than just passing two arguments?

Is it so you can pass the array returned by the get function into the set function in a later patch?

The idea is for the get function to be able to receive as an argument whatever was returned by the set function.

Get() needs to return two things. They need to be packed into something before being returned. Currently it's easy to imagine how you can unpack them and pass as individual arguments to set(). What if I add more things? What if I decide that with more things it's better to return an object from get()? I don't want to unpack such objects for set() arguments.

column14:
My initial guess when I saw the "???" was that it was a way of showing an invalid email - Perhaps there is a better way to show this?

Tracking updates by breaking them into Adds / Deletes on the frontend feels brittle because you are surfacing up what should be a backend implementation detail into the network - what happens if removeUsersFromTeam times out / fails? Or what happens if removeUsersFromTeam passes but addUserstoTeam fails? It is very easy to create some wonky team state on the backend this way. There is no way to ensure the dependence of HTTP calls without significant overhead - this is not a problem on the backend (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Database_transaction).

I was wondering if you considered naively inserting what the admin tells you to insert instead of trying to "backtrack" their actions (In this case, you are trying to figure out what the admin did on the UI and making the corresponding changes in the system). What if you took a list of 4 emails to the backend, and the backend iterates through them, figures out if they are valid and insert the team if all input was valid? Maybe I'm missing something here - let me know what you think.

column14:
I'm happy to see the move from custom CSS to use the built-in bootstrap alert panels and colours. There's a couple of things here that need addressing though: * If the `flash` CSS is no longer required elsewhere, then it should be removed from `common.scss` * Large numbers of tests are failing, since they are looking for the `flash` and `error` css classes. The tests need to be updated. * The contents of this `div` need to be indented. The same with other places where you are wrapping existing code with additional `divs`. Offline and read_only modes are not "danger" messages, since there's nothing that the user can or has done wrong. If we look at the `map_layout` helper in https://github.com/openstreetmap/openstreetmap-website/blob/e443d99edd9c9b68d6c0fa41b028bb9a5cdb07c5/app/controllers/application_controller.rb#L258-L263 we can see that both are treated as `warning` messages For both the offline and edit pages, we end up with "alert"-style banners, but these don't match the flash banners used on the rest of the site, namely: * They don't stretch across the whole page * They don't have the icon alongside the message It would be nice to make them completely consistent, rather than partially consistent. So for example, I would consider reworking this page to use the existing flash messages system to render the alert, for example by using `flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_offline")` in the controller. That way any changes made to flash messages elsewhere (e.g. adjusting margins or paddings) will apply automatically to these offline alert messages. > If the `flash` CSS is no longer required elsewhere, then it should be removed from `common.scss` There are quite a few tests which require the old classes and they were passing on the first test. Would it be OK if I update all instances of the current `flash` classes to `alert` (as well as their tests) or it would it be better to do it in a separate PR? > Large numbers of tests are failing, since they are looking for the `flash` and `error` css classes. The tests need to be updated. I've updated them. Thanks for updating the tests. I'm not sure what you mean with your question for me. I think there is no longer any reason to keep the `flash` rules in `common.scss`, right? I can't see anywhere they are still in use. I'm not exactly sure what exactly needs to be done here. Would this work or the changes need to be made somewhere else? ``` <% if Settings.status == "database_offline" %>

<%= flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_offline") %>

<% else %>

<%= flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_read_only") %>

<% end %> ``` You are right. I was confused since a few tests succeeded even though I didn't update them. They are now fixed. > Would this work Something similar to this actually does work - the trick is that you can add flash messages from a view (since it appears the view is processed before the layout) but you need to avoid also writing the message at the same time. So no `

` tags and no `<%=` outputs. This works: ``` <% if Settings.status == "database_offline" %> <% flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_offline") %> <% else %> <% flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_read_only") %> <% end %> ``` However, I find that a bit unintuitive, since it depends on a timing issue with rendering views vs layouts, and usually flash messages are set in the controller before rendering starts. So I would avoid using `flash.now` in any views. When I said: > for example by using `flash.now[:warning] = t("layouts.osm_offline")` **in the controller** ... I was thinking about changing the `site#offline` method (in SiteController) something like this: ```diff - def offline; end + def offline + flash.now[:warning] = if Settings.status == "database_offline" + t("layouts.osm_offline") + else + t("layouts.osm_read_only") + end + end ``` At this point, the view can be empty, and this will work. Having an empty view is a bit strange, so I would either think of something to put in there (for example, further explanation, but I'm not sure if that is useful) or else remove the view entirely and be explicit in the controller that there's nothing else to render. [I found some examples of how to do this](https://stackoverflow.com/a/45581659/105451), e.g. ```ruby def offline flash.now[...] ... render :html => nil, :layout => true end ``` I did it but it broke that test: ``` # Test the offline page def test_offline get offline_path assert_response :success assert_template "offline" end ``` Do I have to delete the test, since I've deleted `offline.html.erb`? Keep the test, it's still required. The final assertion no longer makes sense and needs to be adjusted - I would change it to no longer asserting that a particular template is used (since we aren't using a view), but to change it to ensure that the layout is still rendered, since we need the layout to make sure the flash message is displayed. There are examples of asserting the layout elsewhere in the test directory. I've updated the test and it seems to be working.

Well, the commit description is misleading – it's not a squash of *all* the commits in the src PR; for instance: the `get_num_acting_pgs()` change is missed.

Instead of a squashing & rewriting, it might be desirable to judge the backportability of dependencies and restrict the differences to just C++20.

I did squash all the commits of this PR. The removed methods in `get_num_acting_pgs()` do not exist in Q. Therefore, it resulted in an empty commit.

The difference is that the changes were not reverted in main - they were fixed in https://github.com/ceph/ceph/pull/49507.
However, in Q, the changes were reverted first and only then fixed (in this PR).

How do you suggest to handle this?

My understanding of events is following:

1. there was a bug fix that introduced a regression to both `main` and `quincy`.
2. In `main` the regression has been fixed by a follow-up while in `quincy` the PR got simply reverted. 
3. Therefore the `check_pg_num()` simplification substantially differs between `main` and `quincy`.

It looks that the quincy version has unsatisfied dependencies (the very original, reverted PR + the regression fix). If so, I would bring those commits again – it still might be clearer than a custom patch.

cherry-picked the reverted commits as well, Thanks for this suggestion!

The commit `mon/OSDMonitor: Make the pg_num check more accurate` lacks the `cherry picked from` info. Use `git cherry-pick -x <commit ID>`. Please also add it's being cherry-picked as dependency for other commits and mention it was reverted.

Needs `cherry-picked from`. What's weird it lacks `Fixes` too. How is it `main`?

`cherry-picked from` + the info why we're taking it.

Far, far easier to review now! :1st_place_medal: 

`Fixes` is missing in main as well https://github.com/ceph/ceph/pull/44430.

Understood.

Sorry, I've missed it last time – this commit is basically a fixup. When backporting the typical practice is to squash such changes while informing the main commit about any customization and the reason for it.

Ack

column14:
Not related directly to this PR: are we not supporting more than 30 branches, then? 😄 

Showing more than 30 options on a select input would not be a very good experience 😄 

The branches are sorted by updated date and the default branch is always on top. If there are more than 30 branches we're forcing the user to type its name because GH API has no search functionality for branches, unfortunately.

The reason we didn't refetch on focus is that if the user switches tabs, they'll lose their current selection 😬

Try it:

1. select a branch that's not the default
2. switch tabs
3. check that the selection is gone and you're back to the default branch

@mpkelly could move that 30 into a constant in this PR. 

I'm the changing the logic which auto selects the branch to check for an existing selection.

I like @zaguiini's idea of changing the type of input based on the number of items.

Regarding the error, I'm in favor of showing the error explicitly, too (especially, since our disabled states for input fields are not accessible). It would be nice to find a less redundant message than the one below, though. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4933/223425816-270b0769-42a9-4152-b643-cbc5d98dc885.png)


> It would be nice to find a less redundant message than the one below, though.

I think we can just leave the text field blank in this case.

A (!) red error is a bit more than I'd expect in this case. There's been no user error they should fix up, they haven't typed anything wrong. It feels more like an informational thing.

But I am definitely in favour of showing a more accessible message!

In general, in Matrix, we don't use integers to represent enumerations.  We usually use a set of string values instead.  e.g. "exclude_sources" can be one of "remote", "local", or "none", defaulting to "none".

While this doesn't mean that endpoints can't use integers, there would need to be a compelling reason for an endpoint to do so, and I don't think that the reason for using an integer is particularly strong in this case.  If you want to allow for the possibility of multiple things to be excluded in the future, the parameter can be made to be an array of things to exclude.

There should be an ["Unstable Prefix"](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/blob/main/proposals/0000-proposal-template.md#unstable-prefix) section

oh, I wasn't aware of that convention. "none" makes little sense, IMHO: If it's a list / set of strings, just keep it empty.

Sorry, I don't understand. Not having written an implementation so far, I did not add that section.

You don't need to have written any implementation yet to define an unstable prefix.  But you should define an unstable prefix for use by anyone who does want to write an implementation.

This seems a bit conflicting to the user... it doesn't actually accept the cookies. This *could* be worse then not telling the user about the cookies, you are implying that they ***can*** opt out of the cookies.  

Another note is that, at least where GDPR applies, you must explain the data that is being collected, saying words such as "like" do not make up a privacy policy. 

Here is an example of something that could be said: 
> This site uses cookies to store data (including, but not limited to, Minesweeper highscores). If you do not agree to the storing of such data do not use this site, or the features that collect such data.

Hear about Alice and her work with us here: 


"I'm a 47 year-old late-diagnosed autistic woman and mother. I am actually multiply neurodivergent: I'm autistic, and I have attention differences. My proudest achievement is that I'm a Mum to my daughter Isabell, who is also multiply neurodivergent. We live together in our home in Brighton with our cat Belle, who I say to my daughter is also autistic - and that's why I picked her, because she's very particular."


"I think something interesting about my profile, which I think is becoming more and more common now, is I've lived life both sides of the river. I've lived for 46 years as a neurotypical person, and I've only lived the past year and a half knowing that I was autistic. Getting a diagnosis was life-changing for me. My motivation wasn't because I needed extra support, it was more because of curiosity, and because of my daughter. My diagnosis came as a positive thing, as a quest of curiosity and self-knowledge, rather than being because I was experiencing problems in my life. So that's actually quite an unusual thing. I wasn't "diagnosed" in that pathology paradigm of something being wrong. So for me, I think that's quite an interesting angle, that my diagnosis was about something more, it was about my strengths - but also so that I could locate some of the challenges that I'd previously experienced in my neurotypical life."

"For me it's just a different way of being in the world, which describes my relationship to the world and people. I always grew up feeling different, and not really understanding why. I had different feelings about things, different reactions to things, and I felt like a refugee actually - which is quite interesting given my work. I felt dislocated and alienated. So when I got my diagnosis I could make sense of why I felt and thought differently. It was validating. A lot of the things I would criticise myself for, like that I couldn't understand things in the same way other people did, or that I couldn't think about things in the same way - can lead to really negative feelings about yourself, which can become a self-perpetuating cycle."

"Some autistic people have quite switched off experiences, but for me, I experience life in glorious technicolour. Don't get me wrong, I'm not seeing things dancing - it's rooted in reality, but I see and feel things very intensely. My particular profile is I'm hyper-sensitive and hyper-emotional. So an example of that would be that if I saw a suffering animal or a dead animal, I would experience pain. My upset will manifest in internal pain, and it will literally be like experiencing high emotions and pain for a couple of days. You're carrying this trauma of this animal with you. So that's an example of how I might experience an event - or something that's difficult or sad. Being autistic can make me different to people, so it can disconnect me - but also, for me, I feel really proud to be autistic. It's given me strength and it's given me power, and being autistic explains my success in life. I'm autistic with attention deficiencies, so for example the impulsivity associated with ADHD can lead some people into negative, painful experiences. That impulsivity led me into something really positive - into risk-taking, because I thought, 'yeah, I'm going to set my own business up'."

"For me, there's both 'despite of', and 'because of' with autism. Being autistic has led to challenges, but it's also opened doors to things and people and worlds I would never have imagined. I feel that it's something that I need to protect and honour and really take care of. It's like harbouring a very precious vase inside of you that you have to really take care of. When I got my diagnosis, it lead to compassion, so my diagnosis gave me self-understanding, and kindness to myself, whereas before I used to be very self-critical, feeling like I was doing things wrong. It was like looking in a kaleidoscope and then being able to switch my whole life, and see my life in a whole new way, going forwards."

"My mates who are in the autistic community are trashing the old pathology paradigm around theory of mind and lack of empathy. Yes, there are some individuals on the spectrum, as there are some individuals not on the spectrum, who may have mental illness and may have a lack of empathy, but then there are people on the spectrum, just like there are people not on the spectrum, who have hyper-empathy, and in fact there's a huge emerging area of research - you have hypo and hyper - you can be more "switched off" and more "switched on", like me, and both can be a gift and a burden. It can be challenging, which is why you need to protect and look out for yourself. So I am of that school of thought, that every day lay notions of autism or autistic people lacking empathy or social skills, it's really old - it's dead."

"With courage, I'm talking to people like you. I'm trying to raise awareness and change the profile, so that across communities and society there are changes in how we perceive neurodiversity. People like me, I have great social skills - I maybe talk too much, but I communicate highly effectively. I'm highly articulate, I have emotionality - a huge emotional landscape, so that I was able to found and sustain a social organisation working with loads of professionals who might have diagnosed me - doctors, psychiatrists, social workers."

"The circles that I'm moving in: I'm moving in academic circles, because of my masters. I'm moving increasingly in professional circles. I am seeing the embracing of the new paradigm. But that has to filter down. So they are the thinkers and the doers in terms of structure. Where I don't see it is in the non-autistic community around me. That's not the case with my friends, luckily - probably because all my friends are neurodiverse, either diagnosed or undiagnosed. Also the kinds of people I would be friends with anyway are really open-minded. But I suppose as I'm navigating day to day life, sadly, there's still these really old misconceptions about autism amongst even the middle class intelligentsia, teachers, and all kinds. There's a lot of work to be done. But I do see it in academic and in organisational and professional circles."

"I wonder, and I think maybe in 50 years time neurodivergent people are going to be the new neurotypicals, because it's such an emerging and growing area, and realising that human nature, what it is to be human, is not singular, and it's not binary. It's not, you know, male and female - gender is a huge construct, ethnicity, race. It's the same with neurodiversity. It's complex, and what it is to be human is not singular."

"That is why intersectionality is so important, and neurology with other categories and dimensions, such as gender and class. Some of what I've been doing in my master's is around reframing and reclaiming those spaces, so you're not just autistic, you're, for instance, neuro-queer. So taking derogatory or pathologizing language and reclaiming it. That's what I'm really interested in, in terms of my research - all this myriad, and kaleidoscope - plus, plus, plus, plus, plus.”

"How I found out about this project was that it came up on Facebook. I'm invested in a lot of autistic organisations, such as The National Autistic Society and Autistica. I'd already looked at Autistica's website and seen a lot of what they did, and I've signed up to be involved in research. I feel this is a natural synergy. This popped up at around 6:30 which is a really random time for me even to be looking at stuff, and I was making something for my daughter, and I thought, "wow, this is interesting". Particularly because the whole sensory aspect of being neurodivergent is massively neglected. I listened to the talk. There were two bits of this: the fact that it's sensory and the participatory aspect - and then the extension of that, which is citizen science - I thought, 'wow'. I like anything which is pioneering, anything that's cutting edge. Because I'm a CEO, I like seeing patterns of what's new and emerging. So I'm involved because I feel that this project is in an exciting, emerging area, and because we know that this is what autistic people have told us feels important to them. It's massively under-researched. So I thought, "yes, I really, really want to do this, I really want to participate in this". I actually feel that it's a commitment and a responsibility to change things for other people, so I really want to be involved."

How much work is generating one of these? Could one be provided out of the box? This plugin could swing between being useful to unusable depending on how difficult this is to setup.

An alternative would be adapters for Maxmind files and allow users to implement adapters for other data sources.

Any GDPR concerns that should be mentioned?

It looks like we could bundle the plugin with a [GeoLite2](https://dev.maxmind.com/geoip/geoip2/geolite2/) database if we need to make it work out of the box. This is a smaller, less accurate free version of their GeoIP database product. The full product requires a license and subscription to use.

I think most of the GDPR rules generally apply to data at rest, i.e., logs, customer records etc. It should be OK to use this data right away in a live website, but it might be problematic to generate logs of who was visiting from where. But if a site logs IP addresses, they could run geoip offline later anyway.

I think using this library has caused problems with the fusion build system since it imports a file from disk (or something like that, I don't recall the details but I think it causes our builds to print out "Warning: custom Babel config is an unstable API and may be not be supported in future releases. Use at your own risk.").

It seems like [node-geoip](https://github.com/bluesmoon/node-geoip) is the most popular JS library for interfacing with the maxmind database. Unfortunately this library requires transforming the database from the maxmind format but says it has better performance. I'm not sure if this is a good time to try migrating to this library.

If there's a benchmark that demonstrates node-geoip is faster, I'm fine with using that. Otherwise, I think it should be OK to use maxmind-db-reader in the near term. We can fork it and/or send a PR upstream to fix the warning.

As far as I know this is not possible to do in SQLite. Also, although this is a small PR, in general forcing a push makes the changes difficult to follow.  Please upload some evidence. 

I noticed this, and changes were made.

I'd use `_sys_hwinfo` as temporary name to be aligned with the previos upgrades.

Please, consider using the following expression when inserting the pre-existent data into the new table (see the rest of the schemas)

```
 INSERT INTO sys_hwinfo_tmp SELECT CASE WHEN checksum <> '' THEN checksum ELSE 'legacy' END AS checksum ...
```

Question: why are we adding a string `"0000"` as `ram_usage INTEGER` ?

It is an unfinished test, I will return to the original.

ok, I'll do it

It seems unnecessary in this update because restrictions are being removed and therefore the existing data will always be valid and with respect to checksum it could not be null because there is a check that prevents it.
In order to the rest, perhaps I can expand why.

>  the existing data will always be valid

Please, always consider that the worst thing can happen and that the data might be invalid.

This PR had to removed some logical and reasonable constraints because the data wasn't valid as expected.

Regardless the `checksum` field, I'm not afraid about a `NULL` value but an empty string `''`.
The thing is that the agents' DB version (11 in this PR) is related to the manager's version but no the agent version.
So it could be the case that a real old agent connects with a new manager, an old agent with the **legacy** syscollector synchronization mechanism that lacks of `checksum` field. 

If an empty string fails to be inserted, the whole upgrade process will fail and the agent's DB has to be re-created, causing a full re-synchronization of the agent/s with this problem.

All the changes we make have to be fully retro compatible. 
That's why we should keep using the expression
```sql
CASE WHEN checksum <> '' THEN checksum ELSE 'legacy' END AS checksum
```

Also, to avoid future hazards, please always follow the same style, structure, conventions, expressions, and procedures pre-existent to the PR in progress unless we have a strong reason to use a new/different approach.





Ok that's right, and thx for the explanation.

We must move to v11 in 4.5 because v10 is used in 4.4.

If we create a new `schema_upgrade_v11.sql` file, then we need to update the version in this file too.

I noticed this, and changes were made.

Typo: `Febrary`

It'd have been more correct to use `int sqlite3_bind = SQLITE_ERROR;`, but no changes are requested. 

Yes, in the middle of the implementation probably I thought of another use for that variable :). Thanks.

column14:
`predecessor_room_id` is a bit wordy but plainly describes what it is and what the value should be 🤷 

```suggestion
(the `m.room.create` event is immutable and can't be changed retroactively).
```

There's another thing to consider here. If we allow a subsequent state event to change the predecessor, then a state reset can potentially reset it to an earlier value, or even make different homeservers observe different values. Moreover, this can happen even without a state reset in case of conditions such as a network split.

Obviously we should eradicate state resets, making this much rarer, but it's somewhat intrinsic to the MSC that situations like this can happen, as soon as we allow dynamically changing the predecessor.

Perhaps this isn't a problem, but I think it's worth mentioning.

I'm a bit worried this MSC introduces higher risk of security issues in clients regarding room takeovers. Currently, the relationship between the previous and current room can be verified (barring state resets), giving the client confidence that room B is in fact the most recent edition of room A. With the relationship being mutable, clients are likely to not check the predecessor correctly and therefore allow someone to hide/take over non-tombstoned rooms.

The current relationship of rooms is very linear, and though this MSC says the mutable event takes precedence, not all clients will have updated to consider that point. This can lead to inconsistencies in what users see, or abusive scenarios where rooms are hidden from some people and not others.

(I think we race conditioned a bit and share [more-or-less the same concern](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3946#discussion_r1062703513), just worded a bit differently.)

I'm slightly more concerned about clients getting the implementation wrong, despite warnings in the spec, though yes: the root issue is "mutable is scary", I think.

Resolving in favor of the other thread, https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3946#discussion_r1062714169

> Currently, the relationship between the previous and current room can be verified (baring state resets), giving the client confidence that room B is in fact the most recent edition of room A.

There is nothing "verifiable" about the `m.room.create` `predecessor` value besides that it came from someone with proper power levels. A Matrix room can be created with whatever predecessor desired (even multiple rooms with the same predecessor). And same for the tombstone from some old room pointing to a new room. And as a note in case onlookers aren't as familiar, tombstones are already mutable.

To me, the chain of tombstone and predecessor are mere suggestions of where you can continue looking at history in the room. I'm not quite following the line of thought to get the severity with danger in any of this.

All of these problems like selectively sharing the state only to certain servers or state resets seem completely separate to this MSC. If we can't trust the state in a room, then everything falls apart.



The presence of a tombstone pointing to the new room and a predecessor pointing to the tombstoned room forms a verifiable relationship - this was specifically designed in for room upgrades. 

With this MSC, we'd be breaking that relationship we previously went out of our way to make verifiable - this is where the concern is coming from. If we're breaking the verifiable nature of the relationship, it needs to be for justifiable/secure reasons. 

We already acknowledge that state resets and similar can cause the relationship to be broken, however the expectation in those cases is that clients actually split the room into two logical rooms again, even if half the relationship still exists. With both halves of the relationship, the client can merge the rooms together safely.

Reference:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1190097/211438371-1fb0aaa6-bc3a-4dcd-ae4f-baa0b1edc34c.png)

In this diagram, if a user is joined to all 3 rooms then what should happen is Room B and Room A are treated as a single room (Room B, specifically), and Room C is treated as its own room. With this MSC, the risk becomes that Room C "takes over" the relationship, thus making all 3 rooms represented by Room C, despite Room B never intending for that to happen.

State resets can also do this, but are a known problem and indeed irrelevant as far as this discussion is concerned.

Are there notes somewhere in the spec or wherever about what you're describing as "verifiable". From usage, it doesn't appear that way to me at all.

I can already create Room C with the predecessor of Room B without this MSC. Nothing seems "verifiable" about that.

`POST /_matrix/client/v3/createRoom`

```json
{
    "creation_content": {
        "predecessor": "!abc:foo.bar"
    },
    "preset": "public_chat",
    "name": "predecessor_test1"
}
```

And this MSC doesn't change the linear linked-list relationship with tombstones and predecessors that already exists.


It's possible to create such a room, just as it's possible to create a tombstone event that goes nowhere (or a room avatar with invalid media reference, or a message without `body`, etc). The current spec is incredibly vague because it was written in an era where that happened more than we would have liked: https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#client-behaviour-27

There might be some history in https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/1791 (the spec PR) as it looks like there was some back and forth on the PR (because that was also legal in the spec process at the time), and the original MSC was https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/1502 (note that it's technically MSC1501, for reasons of process at the time). There's also more discussion at https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/issues/1425 which might be useful.

I haven't looked in depth, but it appears the sentence you're after isn't described explicitly, but rather implicitly. Because the client is expected to make an effort to hide the old room from the user, it is also expected to ensure malicious predecessor structures the user has visibility on do not override rooms (as that would be a takeover). 

The js-sdk's implementation of this verification is togglable, as it somewhat depends on the scenario where it's being used: https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-js-sdk/blob/424212cd6546a00b606380f10ae2585d1d43e518/src/client.ts#L5015

Similar filtering is done by the js-sdk when determining the true set of "visible" rooms (used by the room list algorithms in the react-sdk layer): https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-js-sdk/blob/424212cd6546a00b606380f10ae2585d1d43e518/src/client.ts#L3768

In short, the verification happens client-side at the moment (which is regrettable, but there's much more inferred history to room upgrades that made this reality - I can dig into it internally if interested, though it doesn't affect this MSC).

----

fwiw, some of this concern is driven by the MSC's problem statement: it's not entirely clear what exact problem is being solved here, and some out of band poking has revealed a few more details about the real-world case for this. In practice, it looks like Gitter will be migrating chat history into Matrix and would like to do that in a clean way. The proposed solution appears to be that a MSC2716-compatible room will be created, history imported, tombstoned, and retroactive predecessor set on the already-existing room to point to the MSC2716-compatible room.

Assuming that's accurate (please correct me if not), there are a few concerns/questions/suggestions regarding the approach:
1. In order to guarantee any amount of durability on the imported history, Gitter would need to be using a stable room version to import the history into. Currently, MSC2716 is unstable and Synapse drops unstable room versions when the feature is included in a stable version, intentionally and regardless of usage. This will mean that eventually, when/if MSC2716 gets adopted into a stable room version, the history will be lost to time. It also means the history would only be accessible by Synapse currently, as no other server to my knowledge implements the unstable room version.
2. MSC2716 has a backwards compatibility case to allow importing history into existing rooms, as the room creator. From what I remember, all of the Gitter rooms were created by a service account: this service account could be used to import history into the already-existing room version, therefore not requiring a second room to be involved.
3. If the Gitter service account doesn't have creator access in enough of the rooms, but the Gitter server can upgrade the room, an option would be to upgrade the room in-place to a MSC2716-supported version (ideally stable, for reasons described in no. 1 above), import the history into the *new* room, and continue using the room normally (or upgrade it again for a clean slate): this gives the benefit of time-accurate history (not necessarily DAG-accurate, which clients don't care about anyways) while also requiring no changes to room upgrades. 

The value of a dynamic predecessor is definitely present, I think, though the security concern of room takeovers has me worried. Having written this short thesis of a comment, I don't really have many good ideas on how to fix it right now, but believe it can be done. In the meantime, hopefully one of the suggestions/considerations for the real-world usecase are useful.

> In short, the verification happens client-side at the moment (which is regrettable, but there's much more inferred history to room upgrades that made this reality - I can dig into it internally if interested, though it doesn't affect this MSC).

I don't see a problem where this MSC conflicts with any of this. The client can still do its merging and "verification" as necessary. And the client getting it wrong is not a dire scenario. It just results in two rooms being shown. This "verification" is even toggleable as you mentioned so it's not core to anything.


> fwiw, some of this concern is driven by the MSC's problem statement: it's not entirely clear what exact problem is being solved here, and some out of band poking has revealed a few more details about the real-world case for this. 

The MSC describes the import use case that I will be using this for but it's [not with MSC2716](https://gitlab.com/gitterHQ/webapp/-/merge_requests/2313#why-arent-we-using-msc2716).

For Gitter, we're using the single `/send?ts=123` endpoint with timestamp massaging. We're creating a separate historical room, importing the message history one by one, tombstoning to point to the "live" room and want to use this MSC to have the "live" room's predecessor point back to the historical room.



> > In short, the verification happens client-side at the moment (which is regrettable, but there's much more inferred history to room upgrades that made this reality - I can dig into it internally if interested, though it doesn't affect this MSC).
> 
> I don't see a problem where this MSC conflicts with any of this. The client can still do its merging and "verification" as necessary. And the client getting it wrong is not a dire scenario. It just results in two rooms being shown. This "verification" is even toggleable as you mentioned so it's not core to anything.

A client getting it wrong means the room has been taken over, which is very much against our threat model for Matrix (for better or worse). This MSC allows for dynamic predecessors, but clients trying to apply their verification logic to the linked list will end up treating the proposed usecase as two isolated rooms instead of a single room. 



> > fwiw, some of this concern is driven by the MSC's problem statement: it's not entirely clear what exact problem is being solved here, and some out of band poking has revealed a few more details about the real-world case for this.
> 
> The MSC describes the import use case that I will be using this for but it's [not with MSC2716](https://gitlab.com/gitterHQ/webapp/-/merge_requests/2313#why-arent-we-using-msc2716).
> 
> For Gitter, we're using the single `/send?ts=123` endpoint with timestamp massaging. We're creating a separate historical room, importing the message history one by one, tombstoning to point to the "live" room and want to use this MSC to have the "live" room's predecessor point back to the historical room.

If this could be clarified in the MSC, it would be appreciated. The current intention of the MSC is unclear and appears to tell a different story than what is actually planned.

> A client getting it wrong means the room has been taken over, which is very much against our threat model for Matrix (for better or worse).

How is this a takeover? Above all, this is just a client display thing. And second, it looks like one room needs the tombstone and other one needs a predecessor for things to look replaced. Both sides acknowledged each other for this to happen. Anything other than this seems like a bad assumption on the clients part.

> If this could be clarified in the MSC, it would be appreciated. The current intention of the MSC is unclear and appears to tell a different story than what is actually planned.

I can update it to spell it out more plainly 👍




I'm not sure this is wrong 🤔 (more opinions/knowledge needed)

> How is this a takeover? Above all, this is just a client display thing. And second, it looks like one room needs the tombstone and other one needs a predecessor for things to look replaced. Both sides acknowledged each other for this to happen. Anything other than this seems like a bad assumption on the clients part.

The case I'm concerned about isn't when both rooms point at each other, but rather when a client developer inevitably makes a mistake in the implementation of this MSC. There's already significant risk of clients getting the implementation wrong, and making the predecessor dynamic opens the door wider for mistakes (despite warnings in the spec, which often go unheeded). This would result in a malicious room being allowed to overwrite/hide another room it shouldn't have right to, thus takeover.

"retroactively" is more correct as the subject is being looked at without consideration.

> This would result in a malicious room being allowed to overwrite/hide another room it shouldn't have right to, thus takeover.

This seems like it would be a client doing something very wrong. We can't help a client that doesn't look at both `tombstone` and `predecessor` to see that they match. That's a bare minimum even with the current state of `tombstone`/`predecessor` if you're making rooms look replaced. A client can show the pointer forward/backward without this verification though.

Even a naive client implementation that only looks at the create event for the `predecessor` is safe in the new world that this MSC creates.

If a client implementation updates to look at `m.room.predecessor`, then that is also pretty fool-proof regardless of which era of state they look at. The only tricky thing I could think of is if we also lived in a [MSC3779](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3779) world where someone doesn't check for the canoncial version with `state_key: ""` but that's not a concern yet (and is a general problem).

We seem to use `retrospectively` more often in the spec than `retroactively` in scenarios like this (just searching all of the MSC's in this repo)

Judging from https://english.stackexchange.com/a/148988/103469, it seems like `retroactively` fits better since an action is being taken to change things.

I agree that the client would be doing something wrong, however the risk of a client doing something wrong is higher with an MSC like this (in its current form) that overall leaves an impression that the protocol is insecure, even if the blame is actually with the clients. 

Unfortunately I don't recall all of the details, but there was also a reason why we embedded the predecessor into the create event instead of a dedicated state event: a dedicated state event would have been cleaner and "more proper" as far as Matrix is concerned, but we landed on putting it in the create event for a reason. Digging up that rationale would likely help this conversation, as it keeps coming to mind, though I sadly do not have the bandwidth to do that research.

> I agree that the client would be doing something wrong, however the risk of a client doing something wrong is higher with an MSC like this (in its current form) that overall leaves an impression that the protocol is insecure, even if the blame is actually with the clients.

I don't think this MSC increases the risk level. We have the exact same risk with the current `tombstone`/`predecessor` state of things.

And to address that one aspect, it sounds we should consider another MSC to verify this server-side so clients can more easily rely on eating whatever we feed it.


> Unfortunately I don't recall all of the details, but there was also a reason why we embedded the predecessor into the create event instead of a dedicated state event: a dedicated state event would have been cleaner and "more proper" as far as Matrix is concerned, but we landed on putting it in the create event for a reason. Digging up that rationale would likely help this conversation, as it keeps coming to mind, though I sadly do not have the bandwidth to do that research.

This would be interesting to find. We should start a new thread if we come up with anything here.


One datapoint around verifiability: I found a bug in matrix-js-sdk's code for verifying links: https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-js-sdk/pull/3089 . The fact that this has remained undiscovered for a long time may imply that people are not paying a great deal of attention to verifiability.

@MadLittleMods did you consider including event_id like in the create event? Some code in matrix-react-sdk expects to be able to have that. I'm not sure yet what the implications would be of not providing it when looking for a room's predecessor. (I imagine we can work around it, but I haven't looked into it yet)

> did you consider including event_id like in the create event?

Didn't know about it so no consideration was given to it so far. For my own reference: https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#mroomcreate

> `event_id` (**Required**): The event ID of the last known event in the old room.
> `room_id` (**Required**): The ID of the old room.

Adding an optional `last_known_event_id` field seems fine 👍

I assume it's not related to the upgrade verification part at all since we should be looking at the latest state in the room. But this sort of info could be nice as one option for a continuation point to jump to in the old room.

It terms of workaround fallbacks, we can just go to where the latest tombstone in the old room is or just the latest in the old room. One more complicated option is to use the `/timestamp_to_event` endpoint to find the latest event from when the predecessor was sent but doesn't seem necessary or the right thing to do exactly.


Without a via list this is likely to be unjoinable over federation as room_ids are not routable. https://github.com/vector-im/element-web/issues/2925 for context.

One desired use case with this is to allow users to view and access a predecessor room they haven't been in before, and which their homeserver likely doesn't know about.

@t3chguy Just confirmed my suspicions that to join such rooms, the room id isn't enough, we'd also need the vias or a room alias. Which means the vias should be included at least in the dynamic predecessor message. As the static room predecessor message doesn't include vias either, use of that likely should be phased out.

(As requested, I've moved the comment to a separate thread)

> Without a via list this is likely to be unjoinable over federation as room_ids are not routable. https://github.com/vector-im/element-web/issues/2925 for context.
>
> @t3chguy, https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3946#discussion_r1100243871

(moving this comment to this thread)

This makes a lot of sense! 👍

Added a `via_servers` field to the `m.room.predecessor` event in the proposal

So I understand the use cases, are my assumptions above correct? Are there other use cases? Is this useful?

IMO this should be `via` for consistency with already specced shapes, e.g. `m.space.child`. https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#mspacechild

There is also [`/join/{roomIdOrAlias}?server_name=foo.bar`](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#post_matrixclientv3joinroomidoralias).

I can update this to be whatever name we want to start being consistent about. Thanks for that link, https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/appendices/#routing is also an interesting reference.

I chose `via_servers` because it seemed like the best plainly readable thing and pretty much self-explains what the content should be.



The reasoning for this is that, even if the via servers were specified in the room.create event, they'd quickly go out of date, as the room.create event is immutable.

Whenever via servers change, the dynamic room predecessor event can be updated with new via information, though.

As result, even if the room.create event were updated to include via servers, phasing it out would still be recommended.

We might want to add more of the aforementioned context in the spec as well, potentially as suggested guidance on when dynamic predecessor events should be updated as well.

Added 👍

Thanks for the extra notes!

Not sure the renaming is worth the risk of breaking downstream code using the `galaxy-tool-util` package?

Maybe not. This should - if at all - be done in steps with a deprecation warning announcing the change.

So why did I even do it? Its functionality - or rather the pieces that make up its functionality - are not reused as widely as it could be. When you run `git grep -n '.split(' *.py` in the `mulled` folder, you'll see that the parsing is reinvented over and over again. And I am hesitant to add another version of the parsing of container definitions in a new linting module. So it the intention is not just to rename this function, but to decompose it into reusable parts and reuse them whenever a string is parsed that defines a mulled container.


> Could you also add a unit test if possible?

Unit tests are small examples of the usage case which you fixed with your solution. Before  your fix, these examples should show the error. If you next apply your fix and tries the examples again you should not see the error any more.
By storing these examples as unit tests, we prevent that in the future this problem happens again.

Would it be cleaner to change the default value of def_val to an empty string instead? That way if a caller passes nullptr for def_val, this method will not mess with the expected return value.

Thanks @vedanshbhartia for your feedback, I've just made another commit fixes this.

i looked at the calling code: rgw_rest.h, rgw_auth_s3.h/cc, rgw_rest_client.cc
all of these places interpret `def_val=nullptr` as "not found without default value".
this means, that any change to the return value would break the existing logic.

so, i think there could be several options:
* leave the things as they are (maybe add a commend at rgw_common.h saying that this function returns nullptr if value is not found and default value is not provided. and still have the risk of dereferencing a nullptr
* change the return type to `cosnt std::string&`. since the internal map already holds `std::string`, it may make sense to return it from the function. and pass empty string as the default value
* or, to avoid confusion between an empty string, and a missing value, i would not go for an empty string as the missing value, instead, i would return `std::optiona<std::string>` which clearly indicated whether a value exists or not, and have two overloads of the function, one with a default, and one without


Thanks @yuvalif for looking into the calling code and providing options for the return type of the function. I appreciate your thorough analysis.

Regarding the options you suggested, I understand the potential confusion between an empty string and a missing value. I think using `std::optional<std::string>` as the return type is a good solution as it clearly indicates whether a value exists or not. Having two overloads of the function, one with a default and one without, would also be helpful.

I've chosen the second option replacing by changing the return type to `const std::string&` and made a commit for that.

Please let me know if you need any further changes or if everything looks good now.

Question: Why does this need to be checked if if "pThis->remoteSNI == NULL?
Like in nsd_gtls.c line 2022.

This is actually a slight change to `nsd_ossl`, which currently behaves differently than `nsd_gtls` (if I'm reading the code right.) The change made in PR #1393 to set the SNI based on the hostname, was only made to `nsd_gtls` - so currently, `nsd_ossl` actually has no SNI support at all. I'll update the PR to indicate that this is actually also a feature add to `nsd_ossl`.

But if I'm understanding your question right: the reason to call `SetServerNameIfPresent` even if `pThis->remoteSNI == NULL`, is to set a default SNI (the value of the `target` parameter to `omfwd`, if it's not an IP address) if no SNI is specified in configuration.

Thanks for the explanation (Y).

column14:
I am not agreeing nor disagreeing with the sentiment here, but it is already possible to have partially encrypted events [since `m.relates_to` is always in cleartext](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#forming-relationships-between-events); it does create complexity though of how that interacts with a decrypted plaintext version.

I wonder if it would make sense to have the spec say that a server impl should refuse a cleartext fallback if `m.encrypt` is present.

While this doesn't protect against people modifying their servers this would protect against faulty client implementations. 

On further thinking and talking to people: wouldn't it make sense to even enforce this in the auth rules? Is there any case where checking wouldn't be trivial or where you need plaintext next to encrypted? 

Reasoning behind doing this via auth rules would be that this is a security concern. So this would prevent a security relevant issue which would justify having strict validation of the event imho as security outweighs most use cases I can think of. 

indeed, though the concern is more that someone will stick `m.markup` as a fallback on an encrypted event, which defeats the purpose of encryption. This proposal as-is also theoretically allows for weird parts of the event to be encrypted, though that's not intended to be valid.

At this stage, auth rules feel overly strict for the general protocol: while I can agree with the principle that information should be enforced as encrypted, the general purpose nature of the protocol would call for a less constraining approach. 

Also at this stage, I currently believe that adding auth rules to specific event types would be a design failure. Ideally, there aren't exceptions.

I don't love the variable-type `ciphertext` in the old `m.room.encrypted` schema. Could it be split up into separate fields or something?

The example event uses Olm rather than Megolm. Does this MSC also cover a replacement for `m.room.encrypted` in to-device events?

toDevice is message-based, not event-based. 

Extensible Events does not consider toDevice in scope.

as mentioned in your other comment, it looks like I copy/pasted the wrong example. Not sure we can split up a string.

This will disable CEIP participation for all users using the docker image. We recieve a lot of valuable information for the usage of PowerCLI via the CEIP programme, so we wouldn't like to disable it by default.

Enabling it by default is also not an option, because that causes GDPR issues for people using this as a base image...
And asking is also bad because it blocks script execution.

So the only option is to disable it by default.

The most prudent path is indeed to **disable** CEIP, by default.

```bash
pwsh -c "Set-PowerCLIConfiguration -Scope AllUsers -ParticipateInCEIP \$false -Confirm:\$false" && \
```

**Ryan Johnson**
Senior Staff Solutions Architect | Product Engineering @ VMware, Inc.

taken for introduction - christoph



taken for introduction - christoph

taken for introduction - christoph




taken for introduction - christoph


very interesting / possible tension with earlier proposal? 

I think scenario here is quite important - company collection of data from: 

- their own workers 
- their independent providers / contractors 
- workers for another company, or some other captive / compelled population 
- consumers of their products 

these are all currently different types of data providers, and while it may not be necessary at this point, I think elucidating the difference between these scenarios and the data collected in each one might help address some conflicting perspectives (i.e. remunerate people for their data, but move away from service-for-data business model) - kate

possible connection to labor intelligence / coop-supporting institute proposal - kate

possible tension between this view and later proposal from DSC Wiesbaden re: commercial payment of data providers? I see the proper valuation / remuneration of data being a big topic, and the concern raised by the authors here re: vulnerable populations is quite valid. - kate

there are a number of studies, and teaching methods don't appear to be the main issue - this proposal requires some follow-up - kate

nteresting thought - gets at tradeoff between data protection for content consumers vs utility for value attribution to content creators - kate

a strong claim - not sure that I would endorse in present form / without additional qualifications (just supporting open source doesn't go far enough toward a sustainable model for me). Joren's our IP expert, maybe he can take on this proposal? - kate

Patents also have their useful aspects. I would suggest to work on societal taxes and dividends for redistribution, this way the gains the corps had through public research flows back to the citizen. See also 'European New Deal'. - lynx

ntroductory words --- could be deleted for overviews sake - subliminal guy

Interesting! - subliminal guy

see also Claudio Agosti (vecnas) proposal - subliminal guy

Other pillar? - subliminal guy

I wouldn't want DiEM25 to make such a statement as it would accept and acknowledge that citizen and consumers become more transparent while that isn't actually necessary for anything, it has no societal benefit and should be forbidden by law. Still, even if we defend the privacy of people it is still important for humanity to improve transparency of corporations (other pillar however). - lynx

In my opinion this is only radical prose and not politically clever – We should concentrate on different business models or public funded solutions - subliminal guy

Outlawing advertising is a worthwhile thought. It is rarely ever used to inform us of the existence of some new product and most of the time manipulating us, especially everyone below 20 years of age or so (when advertising actually works best — check research on the subject). This is beyond the scope of our pillar, but we could certainly forbid all kinds of surveillance-based and individualised advertisement built on psychological manipulation by disabling certain features of HTTP and Javascript *by law*. No web browser is allowed to support them. No web server in Europe must try to employ them. - lynx

I was mostly referring to sentences like "People wanting more and not being happy with what they have." Such a statement belongs to blunted discussions in the park while drinking Carlsberg and Beck's and wearing nike sneakers and H&M shorts combined with a "insert-your-favorite-hipster-brand"-shirt

In my opinion this is only radical prose and not politically clever – We should concentrate on different business models or public funded solutions - subliminal guy

I'd largely avoid making rabid remarks about the state of a 21st century consumer brain in a tech policy paper

Outlawing advertising is a worthwhile thought. It is rarely ever used to inform us of the existence of some new product and most of the time manipulating us, especially everyone below 20 years of age or so (when advertising actually works best — check research on the subject). This is beyond the scope of our pillar, but we could certainly forbid all kinds of surveillance-based and individualised advertisement built on psychological manipulation by disabling certain features of HTTP and Javascript *by law*. No web browser is allowed to support them. No web server in Europe must try to employ them. - lynx

But: corporate researchs will need to be rewarded as well – Here we should encourage a different patent system - subliminal guy

One where subsidies are only granted if all research is public? :) - Anonymous

We don't want to censor the (privatized) public sphere, right? What could be a more moderate means to ensure an ad-free public discourse? - subliminal guy

Let's forbid unethical surveillance capitalism rather than de-facto accepting it by running (desperate) campaigns for the "alternatives." - lynx

> industrial-entertainment-military complex 

We should avoid such language in our paper as it is based on non-proven claims and is not helpful in establishing a public discourse - subliminal guy

> sustainable projects

Sustainable in what sense? - subliminal guy

Off-topic? - lynx

Probably true, but do we have scientific material on the subject? And does it belong to this pillar? - lynx

Patchworky proposal. Is there any scientific sociologic backing to doing things this way? Liquid democracy at least has http://arxiv.org/abs/1503.07723 speaking for it. Also, representation doesn't work. - lynx

EC might indeed take care of that, but it is only a secondary problem. The main problem is how the advertising and online markets were allowed to converge onto just 5 gatekeeper companies (plus 2 in China). - lynx

We could require that all smartphone apps must also be usable from any computer. Technically this is already possible, but hardly anyone has an Android emulator on their laptop. - lynx

This seems to be asking for an exchange standard, not a legislation. Standard document formats however exist, also means for upload — so if the industry hasn't established a standard practice in this field maybe that's because they have no economic incentive to do so? A legal policy could make it mandatory for publishing platforms to accept a uniform simple document upload format. Not clear to me which political problem this really addresses. - lynx

If we let humanity live on in the mine field of an unregulated Internet, then we need to spend billions in educating the teachers so that they actually know what they are talking about. Probably easier to change the Internet so that it no longer is a mine field. Then *nobody* has to learn encryption tools, and *nobody* has to understand why they are necessary. The "alternative" would become the default as mandated by legislation (#ObCrypto). - lynx

This is not an accurate description on how the big 5 became monopolies. - lynx

Free/Open Source software was one of the winning ingredients of Google and subsequent monopolists. When it came to making a product they moved the code to the private realm, just like it is described with research above. FLOSS alone is not the solution, it needs supporting legislation. - lynx

DiEM is not in government, therefore it should not confuse electorate with "preliminary" steps. It should promote the long-term vision for fair technology that doesn't suck. Proprietary technology should not be legal for any societally critical applications. - lynx

Copyright abolition would not solve this problem. Content goes viral using one specific URL and whoever has that copy makes all the money. Still, the idea of going back to "broadcast" is very good and the way to achieve could be to (a) make it mandatory to distribute websites by multicast pubsub instead of HTTP (see https://secushare.org/pubsub or IPFS for that), (b) make targeted advertising illegal and (c) introduce a mandatory anonymous micropayment system by which *any* article can be bought anonymously for a few cents. See https://taler.net for the most promising payment system in that regard. - lynx

Yes, and forbid proprietary code in all societally essential systems, therefore giving any programmer on Earth a decent chance to find vulnerabilities by reading *source code* rather than disassembling machine code. - lynx

Oh yeah! We need funding to *create* a truly distributed and private social network. None of the existing softwares can actually replace Facebook *technically*. In most cases they are just yet another server you have to trust. See https://secushare.org - lynx

Why? And is it enough if it is just a right and not an obligation? For the defense of democracy it probably must be mandatory to anonymise or at least pseudonymise digital activity. - lynx

This can actually be solved technically and should be mandated by law. See https://youbroketheinternet.org/programme for details. - lynx

Spare a few details that are too detailed you just pretty accurately described the GNUnet/secushare project.  <3  The YBTI proposals for legislation aim at obtaining this kind of Internet instead of the current borken one. Instead of asking money to be spent in making this system we recommend to make it a necessary requirement so that the entire industry MUST work on solving this challenge: the challenge for an ethically acceptable Internet. - lynx

Breaking up the monopolists would need to be repeated yearly as the digital market tends to recreate new monopolists. The best way to prevent trading of data is to not let anyone *have* any data to trade — otherwise trade will happen, either legally or in the darknet, simply because the data is there and there is no evidence of it being abused or stolen. - lynx

Yes, but how? - lynx

This assumes GDPR actually achieves the goal. See https://youbroketheinternet.org/GDPR for a criticism why GDPR may in large part fail to actually achieve the intended goals. - lynx

Yes I already boiled it down in the actual green paper draft ... Glad you like it, tho ... Most of it comes from Maidsafe's specs. I only added the EU as facilitator ...

It just a detail, more checks are better than less checks

I understand the use of strrchr to avoid splitting a name that may have @ in its name, but given the case we have a name like this random@pkg@1.0, we are removing the version in the data provider functionality, and then here we are removing "@pkg" which interfere with the purpose of the function. 

If the name contains a @ character (I dont know if it is possible...). For example "random@pkg@1.0" the name captured would be "random".
Maybe a helper string function could be created that uses regex to detect this kind of "{package_name}@{version_number}" form. 
Maybe something like this one:
^(.+)@((?:[0-9]+\.)?(?:[0-9]+\.)?(?:[0-9]+))
The first capture group is the package name and the second capture group is version (supports major, major.minor and major.minor.patch forms)


If the name contains a @ character and dont have version number (I dont know if it is possible...). For example "random@pkg" the name captured would be "random" and the version number would be "pkg".
Maybe a helper string function could be created that uses regex to detect this kind of "{package_name}@{version_number}" form. 
Maybe something like this one:
^(.+)@((?:[0-9]+\.)?(?:[0-9]+\.)?(?:[0-9]+))
The first capture group is the package name and the second capture group is version (supports major, major.minor and major.minor.patch forms)

I'll remove these changes and leave only the fix in **syscollector.**

For example, the space `" "` is the default unknown value of **syscollector**. But it ends up being an underscore `_` because vulnerability detector tries to convert all the spaces to match the NVD. So the vendor being a `_` it's almost an accident.

I tried to be generic to avoid a little change breaking the functionality again. 

The version is properly extracted in another section. 
I only need to remove everything after `@` if it's a version.

I make the assumption that in the remote case we have a `@` and a version, it will at the end. 
I'll correct this section.

This class is also used in QuickSubmit, so removing it will require a rewrite over there.

What do you think about using the Laravel service container for things like this? Since we're now namespaced we no longer need the `PKP` suffixes on classes (except for backwards compatibility). We can let the app configure the service container with the appropriate classname when we need to specify it, and have pkp-lib just specify `ContributorForm`. Particularly when there are empty subclasses, I find myself wishing for a better way...

I would rather `is_inactive` be specifiable as a parameter (even if the default is to exclude inactive sections). If I were coding without checking, I would expect `getByContextId` to get *everything*; if that's not the case, autocomplete/hinting should guide the dev to know what to expect.

(BTW, I just merged https://github.com/pkp/pkp-lib/issues/8366 to `main` in OMP and pkp/browse; a doubled check won't cause harm, but just FYI.)

Missing `|escape` (also for `{translate}` call below) -- this one isn't critical, and probably not the one below either, but a good habit and just in case.

Oh no. I see it uses `submissionMetadataFormTitleFields.tpl` and `submissionMetadataFormFields.tpl` too. As well as the `AuthorGridHandler`. All of this has been removed. I see two options: 1) move these files into QuickSubmit (but I have probably removed several locale strings that they use) or 2) rewrite QuickSubmit to use the new wizard as a base. Both seem like a lot of work.

The thing I don't like about using `app(ContributorForm::class)` or `App::make(ContributorForm::class)` is that the return is not type hinted. So it has to be manually annotated:

```php
/** @var ContributorForm $form */
$form = app(ContributorForm::class);
```

The other problem is that if dependencies can't be automatically injected -- and they usually can't be for forms -- then we have to read the code to know what to pass to the service container, rather than having the editor tell us what the constructor expects:

```php
$form = app(ContributorForm::class, [
    'action' => $url,
    'locales' => $locales,
    'submission' => $submission,
    'context' => $context,
]);
```

This becomes especially problematic if the constructors differ between apps. And using different constructor function signatures is a common way to extend a base class in an app.

I think the service container is only good for when we want to do automatic dependency injection. For example, injecting the request, file service, schema service or other singletons into a `Handler.

> I find myself wishing for a better way...

Increasingly, I find that I am writing a helper function in a `PageHandler` that gets a form class, because this can be clearly type-hinted and easily overridden in an app:

```php
namespace PKP\pages;

use PKP\components\SectionForm;

class SectionHandler extends Handler
{
    protected function getSectionForm(Context $context): SectionForm
    {
        return new SectionForm($context);
    }
}
```

```php
namespace APP\pages\section;

use APP\components\SectionForm;

class SectionHandler extends PKP\pages\SectionHandler
{
    protected function getSectionForm(Context $context): SectionForm
    {
        return new SectionForm($context);
    }
}
```

That's a lot of boilerplate. But the base `Handler` is fully decoupled from `APP\components\SectionForm` and everything is nicely type-hinted. If the base `Handler` needs a function that's dramatically different between apps, then `PKP\components\SectionForm` can add an abstract function for it.

In this case, `is_inactive` is a condition of `$submittableOnly`. This was added when inactive sections were added. So historically, `$submittableOnly` meant "can a non-editor submit to this section". 

If I were to add `?boolean $isInactive = false` as a function argument, then it would be possible to call the function in a way that undermines this logic, since even editors can not submit to inactive sections:

```php
$submittableOnly = true;
$isInactive = true;
$sections = $sectionDao->getByContextId($contextId, null, $submittableOnly, $isInactive);
```

We could fix this by changing `$submittableOnly` to `$restrictedToEditors`. But that would be changing the _intent_ of the original function argument.

As a counterpoint: shouldn't we be testing with the file formats most commonly used by our community? It probably makes sense for us to have a whole bunch of file formats for the tests, so I could add LibreOffice versions in addition to these.

Just a preference and an area where I don't mind us staking out a position. But not worth a debate -- carry on as you like.

column14:
to clarify: for this and the endpoint below, the server treats it as a transaction: if one of the rules fails to update (due to not existing, DB error, etc) then *all* rules fail to update (a rollback).

I think this is a great improvement over what the spec allows today. However, one slight shortcoming is that clients would still need multiple calls if they wanted to update rules of different `kind`s. I wonder if that's a use case we should seek to support? E.g. I suppose we could move the `kind` parameter into the body of the request?

Along the same train of thought, this proposal also doesn't allow changing `actions` and `enabled` simultaneously. In both cases the client would be left with the multi-failure mode we're trying to fix. This almost makes me wonder if we'd need a `PUT /_matrix/client/v1/pushrules_bulk`?

I'm somewhat concerned about giving clients too much ability to cause performance issues on the server-side with large bulk endpoints (each push rules change triggers a sync loop poke). In theory, the client can isolate the `actions` and `enabled` calls safely, and encouraging them to do so would be a good thing imo.

Supporting bulk changes across different kinds is an interesting question though: it implies that one or more push rules might be at the wrong level and need redefining or reconsidering. I'm very interested in this sort of usecase :)

> I'm somewhat concerned about giving clients too much ability to cause performance issues on the server-side with large bulk endpoints (each push rules change triggers a sync loop poke). 

Good point, yes. Could the `/sync` triggers be batched up on the server-side so that you only trigger a single time for any bulk request?
 
> the client can isolate the actions and enabled calls safely, and encouraging them to do so would be a good thing imo

The Element iOS app uses an interesting logic here. When you toggle any of the global notification settings on or off, it issues two `PUT`s. One to `/enable` to ensure that the rule is actually on and one to `/actions` to toggle between `notify` and `dont_notify`. I'm not sure if other clients behave similarly but in this case there are two requests tied to a single UI control so isolating them would probably be tricky?

> Supporting bulk changes across different kinds is an interesting question though: it implies that one or more push rules might be at the wrong level and need redefining or reconsidering. I'm very interested in this sort of usecase :)

Yeah, when thinking through it again, I'm actually failing to come up with a reasonable example. You're probably right that this should normally be taken care of by the priority hierarchy of the different rule kinds.

It would only be a single sync trigger, but that's still a large trigger to happen: we're actively avoiding APIs that allow for arbitrarily large requests/responses, and an endpoint which is "too bulk" would ultimately cause excess data to be transmitted. 

As for Element iOS: this sounds like a bug in the client. The client should have a cached copy of the push rules to be able to make decisions on, and the UI control would still be able to represent a failed state: setting actions on a disabled rule prepares it for when it can be enabled, meaning the client can use the enabled/disabled state to determine if something went wrong. A suggested approach would be to set the actions first (where if it fails the client has no-oped the user's request), then enable the rules. If the enable step fails, the UI control can show that easily, allowing the user to try again. With caching, the client can also determine if it needs to change the actions/enabled state of each individual rule it plans to affect.

> It would only be a single sync trigger, but that's still a large trigger to happen: we're actively avoiding APIs that allow for arbitrarily large requests/responses, and an endpoint which is "too bulk" would ultimately cause excess data to be transmitted.

Ah, got it. That makes sense. 👍

> setting actions on a disabled rule prepares it for when it can be enabled, meaning the client can use the enabled/disabled state to determine if something went wrong
