column14:
This example is missing the type and is not a valid matrix event

Your state Event is fine though. 

Having the PL as the state key seems weird to me. I would have expected the mxid. 🤔 As I would want to lookup the tag for the user so I would go by user id since I might not know the powerlevel. 

I think this may not work as there are clients with more than just those 2 options. So it may not always work. What is speaking against letting the displaying client decide the color? 

Roles instead of powerlevels would be imho a note worthy alternative even though there is no msc for it that I am aware of. 

Does this replace `m.room.power_levels`? Or does it add another layer to it? If it adds a layer why not add it within that state Event? 

Who is allowed to set these? I assume only PL>50?

Does an event without associated PL grant the permission? How would it get mapped to those without the powerlevel? The current powerlevel event allows setting specific numbers to specific actions. This doesn't seem to have something like this. 

I think its more of a suggestion. Discord has Roles with Colours and on there a colour is fine on dark theme and bad on light but this fixes that problem kinda but matrix also has infinite UI variants so that problem is more complicated on matrix. 

This is as close as you get to roles without going for RBAC or hacking in full roles that dont matter auth wise. If you ask me. So its an alternative that should be mentioned but still. 

This is clearly a PL Labels MSC and therefore drop in backwards compatible with all room versions and all existing homeserver implementations and clients that follow the spec due to that it will be ignored safely by non implementing stakeholders. 

I don't think this is intended to be a full  event?  It looks like this is just the definition for the `content` of an event.

Not the author but i mean unless this MSC gives a recomendation to change the PL template your client uses this would be arbitrary state PL ofc. 

As addressed earlier. This is clearly a PL tags MSC and therefore makes no authorisation related changes. It only makes it so you can define that users at the PL of 1337 are Elite Haxors or whatever name you want to give to a given powerlevel. This proposal does implicit ranges. I personally would have if this wasnt made written a MSC that does Explicit ranges only. But as mentioned in another comment i dont want to compete with this MSC with my MSC that has diffrences due to the lack of improvements that are worth competing over when they are of potentially dubious value compared to this approach.

I think the idea is that this just gives names to the numerical power levels, rather than trying to introduce a new permissions system.  So, say I have PL100 in a room via the normal power levels mechanism.  Then the client can look up the appropriate `m.room.power_level_tag` and find out that in that room, with PL100, I am to be referred to as "The Absolute Ruler".

Rather than using one state event per state key, you could put all the labels in a single event, with a map from PL to label.  e.g.

``` jsonc
{
  "type": "m.room.power_level_tags",
  "state_key": "",
  "content": {
    "100": {
      "name": "Admin",
      // ...
    }
  }
}
```

Please wrap your lines to ~80-120 characters

Ah yeah it just seemed weird as the state event is in full

My only concern is event size overflow. Maybe we should restrict the name value to like 50 character?

Most of the client use white and black backgrounds so both these properties make sense to maintain good color contrast for most usecases.

I agree its very common for clients to have darker themes and ligher themes. So offering a way to accomodate this i think is a good idea. 

My concern is just that dark and light is a spectrum not a constant. You can have dark and light and yet have different bg colors in clients. And with that you end up running into accessibility issues where the contrast might not be enough. (see accessibility spec for html/css World which needs a surprising large amount of contrast. So it is easy to mot have enough.) 

I personally think that we cant do too much to mittigate accessibility issues caused by user definable colours. I think that the obvious fix accessibility wise is an accessibility option that disables this customisation venue. 

Possibly.  I'm not suggesting that the alternative that I gave is better (or worse) than what you suggested, but it should probably be listed as an alternative, so that the pros and cons can be discussed.  The reason I suggested that alternative is because it is more similar to how some other state events work (notably the power levels event itself), so it seems to be an obvious way to do things.  Though of course, obvious doesn't mean better.

Alternatively we can only use a `hue` (0 - 360) property to supply a base color and let the client decide how much saturation and brightness they want to add so it stay accessible in their design system. But this will limit the color choices.

How about providing translated names? Right now clients like Element translate the names into the user locale, so making this a map would be interesting. For example

```json
{
  "name": {
    "en": "Guest",
    "de": "Gast"
  }
  ...
}
```

The key would be an ISO locale code. If the requested locale is missing, we would need some kind of fallback to other locales, in the end falling back to `"en"`.

It looks like this is going to be user input so translation does not make sense here. A community can label users with certain power level anything.

Well multilingual communities should be supported since they might bring translations for all langauges they use. For example a community for the Swedish Speakers in finland might bring a Swedish, Finish and English translation for their roles. And in more corporate usecases this will also be able to be utilised properly.

In our case it is a cooperate use case, where multi-language role names are important. Right now it is solved by forking clients and replacing the translations with custom ones.

There is an RBAC MSC in #2812 that could be an alternative, but I think that implementing this MSC is a lot smaller than replacing the power levels with an RBAC system.

@FSG-Cat How do you propose managing these translations? Since this is user input, and only some users can edit state events then only those will be able to translate them. Plus this makes the UX of roles in a client very complex and on top of that since power levels are room-specific, translating those in each room will be an extra burden. 

IMO, if a community wants to add a multi-lingual role for say administrator with PL 100, they can create a Tag with name administrateur and PL99 and add those accordingly to users.

> Plus this makes the UX of roles in a client very complex

UX wise, you probably can default to a single language mode and allow multi-language flows for advanced users. Most people probably only require a single language. 


> @FSG-Cat How do you propose managing these translations? Since this is user input, and only some users can edit state events then only those will be able to translate them. Plus this makes the UX of roles in a client very complex and on top of that since power levels are room-specific, translating those in each room will be an extra burden.
> 
> IMO, if a community wants to add a multi-lingual role for say administrator with PL 100, they can create a Tag with name administrateur and PL99 and add those accordingly to users.

@kfiven I fail to see how the UX would be too complicated because of this. But lets put that besides for now. The translations would be community managed because its a Bring your own Translations system. Also on the note that its room specific yes and no. Its room specific but you can template this and like tbh PL sync is going to be a thing at this rate. I have personally thought about writing the MSC for it.

Also as for your using diffrent PL fix i say that is a wholy unacceptable compromise compared to the slightly more complicated UX or requirement to use specialised tooling like the Feline Matrix Assistant that i made or Matrix Wrench etc. Like its not a compromise that gets you this specific feature at all. You get forced to give admins a rank list as in who can demote who and also you also make it so their tag name is only accurate in a single language per admin meaning you cant know what their role is supposed to be in your language even if said community can translate into it unless said language is the language used for that admins tag. 

Also just to clarify on the nature of these translations. They are not translations where you try to cover all languages on earth. They are translations where you cover the languages used in your community. Therefore it does not matter that its limited scope as to who can write.

I mean how will the client developers know which community wants which language in their PL translation, so clients have to suggest ISO codes of all languages. If we left it empty then it's up to the user to find out those, which again is bad UX for not-so-technical users.

On top of those, this introduces a parallel translation option to the one client uses to translate its interface, which is again bad UX for translators.

Lastly, I feel translating a state event is fundamentally wrong because with this logic a room name also could be another candidate for such translation, and room topic too.

Could we partially solve this by defining default tags that we can then refer to by for example instead of using `"name" : "Moderator"`, we use `"default_name" : "Moderator"` to instruct the client to localize? A selection of maybe 5 different tags will be plenty for most use cases and only the remainder would have to deal with translating the tags themselves.

[mon]
k = v

[global]

column14:
For moderation, another alternative to account deactivation is [shadow bans](https://matrix-org.github.io/synapse/v1.39/admin_api/user_admin_api.html#shadow-banning-users) to essentially lock the person out from sending any events although the user gets no feedback on purpose in this case.

Not a good candidate for other non-moderation cases through.

We would like to hide locked users from the user directory, should it be added to this MSC or left as an implementation detail ?

If left as an implementation detail I am thinking of providing an option in synapse to tweak the behavior.

Yeah, if I remember correctly the initial reason that triggered this work was trying to make Synapse's [account validity](https://matrix-org.github.io/synapse/latest/modules/account_validity_callbacks.html) feature not use an [out-of-spec error code](https://github.com/matrix-org/synapse/blob/07d7cbfe69c239a7ffe5668c1166799370eef0d6/synapse/api/errors.py#L73).

A use case could be that an organisation might require its members to verify their activity within the org by clicking a link sent via email every few months. In which case it is desirable to visibly lock the user out of their account if they don't click the link before a set grace period ends, but it isn't to deactivate their account because they might e.g. be on holiday and should be able to recover it by clicking on said link when they come back.

I won't update the MSC with this clarification (since I'm abandoning it, see https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3939#issuecomment-1618816306), but if you think that would be helpful to add it in (which I would tend to agree with) feel free!

My personal opinion is that this sounds like an implementation detail to me.

I’ve been thinking about an alternative to returning JS source code. Instead, the aggregator could return a serializable value that gets registered. I suppose in this case, the compiler plugin must provide a token (probably in the form of a path to a file that exports the token).

Then the package containing the compiler plugin could easily consume the aggregated values via the DI system.

Some nice properties of using the DI system:

1. If a buildtime token is not registered but is depended on (not using fusion-CLI, for example), there’s an error.
2. Since buildtime values can be easily transformed or mocked using their associated token.

This `ActionLink` is only used in *Broadcasted notifications*, which are generic, and this is a naive attempt to support "Actions" or "Buttons" that can register specific actions.

For example, imagine creating a survey that gets displayed to every user (as a broadcasted notification), and there are a couple of options, those options could be links to a potential API endpoint (inside or outside Galaxy) that register the response. 
Or another example is when you click "Agree" on a privacy policy or cookie agreement. There would be an `agree` action link that points somewhere to read the terms, etc... But maybe it is too generic... :thinking:

"if `job_config_file` was not set (which means it's the default) AND its current value points to a nonexistent path (so the default path does not resolve to a file), then *set it to its default value* (but we've just checked it!).

The value of `job_config_file` does not change in `config/__init__.py` if it is not set. If it *is* set, and we can't find it, we check against root - but that's it.

To keep the examples consistent with how you usually set options and how we have it documented in our guides, we should favor using environment variables when doing container/k8s. 

It should be possible to use `quay.io/keycloak/keycloak:latest` as a base image and copy from it.

```
FROM quay.io/keycloak/keycloak:latest AS keycloak-base

FROM fedora:latest
ENV LANG en_US.UTF-8

# copy dist from base
COPY --from=keycloak-base --chown=1000:0 /opt/keycloak /opt/keycloak

RUN echo "keycloak:x:0:root" >> /etc/group && \
    echo "keycloak:x:1000:0:keycloak user:/opt/keycloak:/sbin/nologin" >> /etc/passwd

RUN dnf update -y && \
   dnf install -y --nodocs java-17-openjdk-headless

USER 1000

EXPOSE 8080
EXPOSE 8443

ENTRYPOINT [ "/opt/keycloak/bin/kc.sh" ]
```

It would also be nice if the example could download the artifacts directly from Maven Central and add them to the providers dir?

I'm not sure but, in your example, is the `keycloak` user running the process?

But if you do not want to invest time on this example, feel free to ignore the comments.

Let's not read the file from the filesystem on each method call. We should instead either store the names in memory, or load them all at startup and store them in memory.

I would vote for the simpler implementation of just loading them all as a JavaScript variable at startup (so no filesystem access at all.)

This strikes me as a potentially expensive query. Do you think we could come up with a less expensive way of generating these names?

Some ideas:
- Generate names in a sequential manner, so we always follow a particular order
- Generate names by hashing the user's email, and somehow associating the hash with the anonymous name (not so anonymous anymore perhaps?)
- Preload a randomized list per queue, hold it in memory as long as the queue is running, and sequentially pop from it (can you think of where this might fall short? Consider that we may run on more than one host.)
- Can you think of other ways?

(Also, validate my assumption; is this actually expensive?)

---

Separately, storing the name mapping at the queue level solves this issue, but introduces other issues -- see my comment on the PR for more.

Would be nice to move this logic to a lib file.

Consider that we can have more than one student (and thus anonymous name) per ticket.

Also, let's lean towards specificity and verbosity in database models... no need to shorten variables!

s/hiddenFields/protectedFields/?

Also, we can use modern JS features to minimize our dependency on underscore. This part can be written as:

```js
Object.assign(Meteor.users.publicFields, { ... });
```

Let's not expose all of `services.google`, only the fields we expect users to need.

As a meta note, I wonder if it's better to make `publicFields`, `privateFields`, and `hiddenFields` mutually exclusive. That way we combine them at the publication level. Thoughts?

Do we need to publish `services.google.email`?

As noted in the PR comment, we could avoid subscribing to the users altogether.

This subscription should probably be at the queue level, if at all?

If we want to filter by both user IDs and course ID, let's create a new publication called `users.byIdsAndCourseI`. I'm not fully convinced we need this though.

This list is awesome! Where did you find it?

"Andy" 

🤔 

Let's skip this guy since it's a two-word animal.

🎃 🙅‍♂️ 🐕 

I wanna say we should skip two word animals... but Nyan Cat though.

I don't think this is too expensive. How many tickets are active in the largest queues? 100? And this is run each time a ticket is created so in a queue with 100 active tickets we'll end up requesting 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + 99 + 100 = 5050 tickets from mongo over the course of the time it takes to create these tickets (which could be something like an hour). I think this is well within the bounds of what mongo and meteor are capable of handling. I don't really think any of the ideas you listed are good solutions and I don't think coming up with a better solution is worth the effort at this point (premature optimization is the root of all evil).

Won't `Object.assign` modify `Meteor.users.publicFields`?

Do you have any idea which fields that would be? There are several ids/tokens in there and I don't know what they're used for. I couldn't easily find anything online either.

Do we ever plan to use them separately? I imagine we'd want to combine them every time we use them, so it would be easier to just combine them when they're created and not have to worry about it later.

I copied them from http://www.grammaruntied.com/blog/?p=1175 but excluded the more negative ones.

I don't think it'll cause any problems...

`RUN apk add --no-cache git libcap shadow`
Removes the need to run `apk update` and to remove package lists after.

Why not group all of these `RUN`s into one layer like the existing image?

Splitting it up (from my limited knowlege) allows if you change the lower ones the upper ones will be cached, meaning you won't have to run the higher ones nearly as often. Perhaps I missunderstood that though.

@justgage there is a great Dockerfile best practices article here.  I thought I would pass it along.
https://docs.docker.com/develop/develop-images/dockerfile_best-practices/

Following these recommendations, specifically for [RUN](https://docs.docker.com/develop/develop-images/dockerfile_best-practices/#run), it will create a more readable Dockerfile:
```
FROM golang:1.9-alpine

RUN apk add --no-cache \
    git \
    libcap \
    shadow \
 && addgroup -g 1000 -S freegeoip \
 && adduser -u 1000 -S freegeoip -G freegeoip

COPY cmd/freegeoip/public /var/www
COPY . /go/src/github.com/apilayer/freegeoip

WORKDIR /go/src/github.com/apilayer/freegeoip/cmd/freegeoip

RUN go get -d \
 && go install \
 && setcap cap_net_bind_service=+ep /go/bin/freegeoip

ENTRYPOINT ["/go/bin/freegeoip"]
USER freegeoip

EXPOSE 8080
```
Notice that the ADD was changed to a COPY as per the recommendation here on [transparency](https://docs.docker.com/develop/develop-images/dockerfile_best-practices/#add-or-copy).

Snapshots should be iterated over with `m_image_ctx->image_lock` taken for read.

This doesn't ensure that the snapshot is in fact primary.  Separately, I think we need to ensure that the snapshot doesn't belong to a different peer.

It appears that snapshot removal here is a fire-and-forget thing?  And that there can be potentially more than one in-flight since the loop in `scrub_incomplete_snapshot` isn't broken out of on the first match?

This is really dangerous because use-after-free can ensue if the rest of `CreatePrimaryRequest` gets done before `handle_scrub_incomplete_snapshot` is called.  Or, vice versa, `finish` might get called underneath a running `CreatePrimaryRequest` if snapshot removal fails.

```suggestion
exec docker-php-entrypoint apache2-foreground
```

don't keep the process around, this also a common problem of signals not routed to pid=1

this is already done in `ENTRYPOINT`, no point duplicating it here.

```suggestion
COPY --chmod=755 ./entrypoint.sh /usr/local/sbin/entrypoint
```

no need to have two layers (COPY and RUN) with recent enough docker.

It's best to rename not to be so generic name, so in case you want/need to wrap and execute another one, like you do with the php entrypoint:

```sh
exec docker-php-entrypoint apache2-foreground
```

if the parent image also had it named as `entrypoint` you would need to make workarounds.

Hence, I propose to use a file named `dokuwiki-entrypoint` when installing (doesn't matter how you name it in your git repository).

```suggestion
RUN set -x && \
    mkdir -p /overlay/original && \
```

I like the shell to show what commands are executed, eases debug and has no downside for the final image.

column14:
What you are describing below is a mapping to an integer. That's however not what the ordering fields were supposed to be for. They are actually an implementation of a floating point number, since you can always insert new characters to insert something in between the previous 2 elements. Hardcoding some integer conversion would be somewhat limiting then imo. Can you show some existing implementations that actually do, what you described? In the end lexical strings can always be compared correctly without converting them to numbers.

> since you can *always* insert new characters to insert something in between the previous 2 elements

Yes, this works, until you hit the character limit, then you have to get more creative.

> Hardcoding some integer conversion would be somewhat limiting then imo

How so? This algorithm creates a one to one mapping between a string and an integer, so limits stay the same. (Assuming the language uses some big integer implementation of course).

> show some existing implementations that actually do

Sure! In the [MSC](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3230) I referenced, there's
- [Element Android](https://github.com/vector-im/element-android/blob/3dc7a6dc3411452f4a7a1531081e3e970574e1b3/matrix-sdk-android/src/main/java/org/matrix/android/sdk/api/util/StringOrderUtils.kt#L78) which creates collisions as multiple strings map to the same number. For example "A" and "AA" are both 0 when they should be 1 and 2 respectively.
- [Element Web](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-js-sdk/blob/9c8093eb3e140385c8f1a5763e0c0a099584238b/src/utils.ts#L551) which creates gaps as the strings don't map to a contiguous set of numbers. For example "A" and "AA" map to 27 and 36 respectively. The gap is problematic when doing midpoint calculations as you can imagine.

> In the end lexical strings can always be compared correctly without converting them to numbers.

Comparison is easy to do correctly but calculating the midpoint between two strings is not and that is what I'm solving with this MSC.

> How so? This algorithm creates a one to one mapping between a string and an integer, so limits stay the same. (Assuming the language uses some big integer implementation of course).

You would need to resend all space children events whenever you reorder rooms. The current implementation allows for resending just a single event.

I'm not sure where I lost you but this MSC doesn't affect the number of events sent. Element Web and Android currently convert the order strings to integers but they're doing it wrong. This MSC proposes a correct way to do the conversion.

Currently space events have an ordering, which uses these strings. Lets assume you have 2 elements, using 2 consecutive strings:

- A
- AA

Those map to 1 and 2 using your algorithm. Now you want to insert into the middle of those. Using your algorithm, you would need to renumber AA, because you don't have fractions:

- A
- AA <- new element
- AAA <- renumbered

With the current spec, you can inset a new Element without renumbering

- A
- A0 <- new element.
- AA <- no renumbering

This always works as long as the first and second Element are not both of the max string length (50) AND have a distance of only 1 or the second Element is not a single space. You have to be very intentional to break that.

Your algorithm however makes it very easy to break by accident. If only "", "A", "AA" are the 3 smallest numbers, then clients will start making the first space in a list "", and the second one "A". Then moving any space up  to the top there means you need to renumber everything after it.

You can still make broken orders in the existing spec, that need lots of reorderings to update the space list, but I would say with your approach it is significantly more likely. Yes, the existing spec makes the midpoint calculation harder, but only if you want an exact midpoint. In most cases finding some string in between is already enough.

I guess you could fix that by not making the mapping strict integer mappings, but still allowing the floating behaviour where you can just make the original string longer to add more insertion points, but currently your proposal removes that.

I've gone back to reread my MSC and I think I see where the confusion is from.

> For the sake of simplicity, I will be limiting the range of characters to be just A, B and C with a limit of 3 characters.

This limitation I stated here was for the sake of explanation. I'm not actually saying we should change the dictionary that's currently use in the spec, I'm saying that the explanation below will use a small dictionary just so it's easier to comprehend.

> With the current spec, you can inset a new Element without renumbering

0 isn't a valid character in my example so you wouldn't be able to use it.

> Your algorithm however makes it very easy to break by accident. If only "", "A", "AA" are the 3 smallest numbers, then clients will start making the first space in a list "", and the second one "A". Then moving any space up to the top there means you need to renumber everything after it.

I could say the same thing for the existing spec's dictionary.
The existing algorithm however makes it very easy to break by accident. If only "", " ", "  " are the 3 smallest numbers, then clients will start making the first space in a list "", and the second one " ". Then moving any space up to the top there means you need to renumber everything after it.

> Yes, the existing spec makes the midpoint calculation harder, but only if you want an exact midpoint.

I'm not changing the difficulty of midpoint calculation (this algorithm definitely wasn't the easiest to come up with), I'm just fixing a common bug in one of the steps.

> In most cases finding some string in between is already enough.

Sure, but who wants to deploy code that only works most of the time, instead of all of the time.

> I guess you could fix that by not making the mapping strict integer mappings, but still allowing the floating behaviour where you can just make the original string longer to add more insertion points

I'm not sure what your issue is with strict integer mappings but when you have a max length and a finite set of characters, the set of all possible strings is finite. Which means you can represent every possible string with a unique integer.

> but currently your proposal removes that.

No it doesn't. My proposal provides a reliable way for clients to do midpoint calculations correctly.
It is up to clients to make sure that when they assign order strings that they do it in an evenly distributed fashion to allow plenty space for inserting without renumbering.

See this thread [here](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3230#discussion_r651809451). The "Recommended algorithm to compute mid points:" section is precisely what I'm trying to fix. Nothing more, nothing less.

May be out of scope for this MSC, but I know when we delete a device we clear its pending todevice messages from the homeserver where it's the destination device, could we also clear out any todevice messages where they are the requester? 

Yes, that would make sense too.

It's a bit frustrating that we need to set out special rules for each type of to-device message, rather than laying out a generic framework for cancellable and expiring to-device messages. It feels like something of a layering violation, and feels like we're always going to be extending this list (with consequent extra work for server implementations).

I would extend this to include semantically equivalent to-device messages. There's real world evidence that some clients will send request cancellations with the exact same request ID / requesting device ID many (>40) times.

I'm going to implement this in the sliding sync proxy because it is aligned with the core bandwidth / speed goals of MSC3575. Before implementing this though, I did some analysis on the size/kinds of to-device events that stack up on the proxy for clients:
 - The largest stack had a huge 237852 to-device events pending. This is uncommon, and rapidly drops off. The median is somewhere in the 100s.
 - Breaking down by event type, the vast majority by several orders of magnitudes are `m.room_key_request` events:
```
         event_type         | count  
----------------------------+--------
 m.room_key_request         | 121067
 m.room.encrypted           |    256
 m.secret.request           |     51
 m.key.verification.cancel  |     16
 m.key.verification.request |     13
```
 - By following the semantics in this MSC, I found that:
```
28089 to-device messages
14495 unique device|req_id tuples
1564 outstanding requests
12931 cancelled requests
260 multi-cancelled requests
potential savings: removing 26525 messages or 94.431984050696 %
```
- "multi-cancelled" requests are identical request cancellation events for the same request ID / requesting device ID.
- The 94% figure is consistent on large (100,000s events) accounts as well as mid-range (10,000s events) accounts. The smaller the stack, the less the benefit. On a device with 204 pending events, this MSC would remove 99 of them (48%).

There is real and immediate benefit to be had by implementing this MSC everywhere, particularly for `m.room_key_request` events which is the event type I did this analysis on.

column14:
```suggestion
If the message edits were allowed by other senders than it would be useful to
```

It may be worth mentioning that it's especially bad with `@room` messages that currently re-notify many people in a room (most of the time noisily as well).

Oh, yes that does make it worse. 👍 

Since this matches on dotted keys, it might run into issues because of https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3873

Probably it is not an issue, since the m namespace is reserved and as such there should be no field with an "m" key. However, this might cause trouble when 3873 is merged, since this is the first pushrule matching on a dotted key, afaik.

It might be fine to ignore that on this MSC, I just wanted to mention it to be safe, if anyone has any smart ideas about it.

Thanks! I've included this under the potential issues section! 👍 

Another potential issue is that this breaks the use case of editing a message to include an additional push target. For instance, if you write a message and then edit it to put another user pill in it, in this case the user would not be notified.

An alternative solution would be to add a push rule with no actions and a condition to check whether a notification should have been generated for the user in the original message (following a capped number of `m.relates_to` jumps).

This should be placed as an override rule before the `.m.rule.contains_display_name` and the `.m.rule.roomnotif` [push rules](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#push-rules).

This seems significantly more complicated for an edge-case (IMO). Is it that common to edit a message to add another person?

It's worth noting that currently we have:

 1. `.m.rule.master`
 2. user-added override rules
 3. other default override rules.

Could you be more explicit about where in this ordering you think the new rule should go? The implementation at https://github.com/beeper/synapse/blame/beeper/rust/src/push/base_rules.rs#L98-L114 seems to put it at the start of (3), which seems about right?

Yep, that's where I'm thinking it should go! 👍  I'll re-word to be more explicit.

```suggestion
This rule should be placed before the [`.m.rule.suppress_notices` rule](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#default-override-rules)
as the first non-master, non-user added override rule.
```

```suggestion
A new default push rule is added to suppress notifications due to [edits](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.5/client-server-api/#event-replacements).
```

```suggestion
The rule is ambiguous (see [MSC3873](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3873))
```

I agree this is an edge-case and I think we can descope it.

another issue seems to be around mobile clients, which might display a notification message when a DM is received, on the back of a push notification.

Currently, the mobile clients receive a push after each edit, which means they can update the text of an on-screen notification to show the updated content. The new push rule will of course inhibit the push, so the mobile client gets stuck with the old content.

I'm much of the opinion this is an unavoidable result of us trying to do too much magic with push rules, and that the new behaviour is probably a lesser evil. Still, worth calling out.

Good call. I've included some of that in the text.

I'm really starting to come around to needing to separate pushing vs. notifications, but that's quite a large change.

Maybe this goes without saying, but since MSC3873 is also proposed for FCP, I think the collision of these two MSCs is fairly obvious: we would update the `"key"` to be `"content.m\\.relates_to.rel_type"`.

Do I need to call this out at all?

I added some info into the alternatives section about this.

I fleshed out the potential issues section a bit more. Thanks!

I fleshed out the potential issues section a bit more. Thanks!

Thinking on this more, I wonder if this MSC is even necessary if MSC3952 lands. In that MSC we wouldn't create mentions *unless* the user is explicitly in `m.mentions: {user_ids: [...]}`. If you edit a message the edited content goes into `m.new_content`. This does mean we could reserve the top-level `m.mentions` for mention information:

* If it isn't provided (or is empty, in compatibility mode) then no mentions.
* But a client could optionally provide it if e.g. they added a new person to the original message, which case they could mention *just* that person.

It does put a bit more onto the client generating the message, but is a bit more stateless.

WDYT @anoadragon453?

Yeah, I'd say it's probably worth adding a sentence saying what the `key` would be under MSC3873.

This sounds to me like a reasonable solution.  The editing client can set the `m.mentions` so that it pings people who have been added, and avoid re-pinging people who have already been pinged.  Or it could maybe have the option to re-ping someone if the edit is significant and the sender thinks the recipient needs to re-look at the message?

@mscbot concern does MSC3952 make this unnecessary?

Thanks @uhoreg! Was just coming to cross-link https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/blob/clokep/intentional-mentions/proposals/3952-intentional-mentions.md#impact-on-edits

This *might* still be useful as a short-term fix until clients start sending (and understanding) the `m.mentions` property?

I agree that MSC3952 could essentially replace this MSC, but that it would take longer to propagate.

I fear that there may be a likely scenario where a client ends up in a world where both intentional mentions and the `.m.rule.suppress_edits` push rule proposed by this MSC exist. Perhaps if the homeserver has added this push rule and the client itself supports intentional mentions.

In that case, the user of that client would not receive (unencrypted) notifications even if an edit explicitly added them to the `m.mentions` array, as the `.m.rule.suppress_edits` push rule would end up suppressing it.

Having both MSCs around at once may create a scenario where clients have to implement logic to explicitly disable the `.m.rule.suppress_edits` push rule in order to not break the use case of mentioning a user only in a message edit.

The only way I could see getting around this is by adding another condition to `.m.rule.suppress_edits` that the event does not contain an `m.mention` array in the `content`, effectively disabling this MSC if the sender of an event is using intentional mentions.

Do any other @matrix-org/spec-core-team members have thoughts on this concern?

Er, my thought is that short-term fixes to the push rules system end up making it even harder to reason about than it already is. If we think MSC3952 makes this redundant, then I would vote that we focus on getting that through. We've lived with spurious notifications from edits for four years; what's another few months?

Another argument in *favor* of this is that there may be other push rules that match the edit; mentions are just a subset of why you might get a duplicate notification, e.g. if you have keywords configured (or set a room to notify you for each message) then you would still get duplicate notifications without this MSC.

In light of @anoadragon453's concerns though, maybe this should be made a lower priority rule than some of the others.

Playing with the priorities a bit to try and work with MSC3952 I think would make sense. MSC3952 doesn't have the formal confidence written down yet, but given the context from other places it seems likely to be successful enough to be worth considering as a complimenting MSC.

Alright, so moving this down in priority...:

1. We still want things in `m.mentions` to potentially cause a notification (so we have to be after that).
2. We likely wouldn't want to be binged for keywords multiple times, but of course *do* want to be binged if an edit adds a keyword...

Hm, this makes me wonder if @anoadragon453 was onto something with:

> An alternative solution would be to add a push rule with no actions and a condition to check whether a notification should have been generated for the user in the original message (following a capped number of `m.relates_to` jumps).

I think that we will likely need to separate pushing vs. notifications in order to properly handle dismissing notifications on mobile platforms when the message is read on another device.

Taking into account intentional mentions (MSC3952), I think what we want to do is move this to be the first *under*ride rule (instead of the first *over*ride rule). With that the following could occur:

* Invites, tombstones, user, and room mentions should continue causing highlight notifications. ✅ 
* Edits to invites and tombstones would still result in a highlight notification (are edits of state events even valid?) ❌ 
* Legacy mentions would still result in highlight notifications. 🤷 
	* Edits to intentional mentions would not result in notifications due to MSC3952 logic. ✅ 
* Keywords would still result in notifications ✅ 
	* Edits to events with keywords would also result in notifications. ❌ 
* Edits to calls, messages, encrypted messages, messages in 1-to-1s, encrypted messages in 1-to-1s would all no longer notify. ✅ 

That all sounds good except for the edits to events with keywords. To get around that we could put the rule as the *last* override rule, so after `.m.rule.room.server_acl`. With that change we would fix the edits to events with keywords being an issue. Edits to invites / tombstones might still cause a notification, but I think that would be very uncommon?

That landed so I've updated this. 👍 

@anoadragon453 I'd be curious if the current reading of the MSC sounds good? I think it hits all your concerns.

> (are edits of state events even valid?)

technically yes, but silly and does nothing of value. The `m.new_content` isn't applied for things like event auth, so you're still dependent on the top level `content` keys existing, making it less effort to just `PUT` a new state event instead of crafting an edit.

> > (are edits of state events even valid?)
> 
> technically yes, but silly and does nothing of value. The `m.new_content` isn't applied for things like event auth, so you're still dependent on the top level `content` keys existing, making it less effort to just `PUT` a new state event instead of crafting an edit.

The spec says it is [not valid](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.7/client-server-api/#validity-of-replacement-events):

> The replacement and original events must not have a `state_key` property (i.e. you cannot edit state events at all).


👍 (/me flips table as Ctrl+F failed to find that)

(just in case anyone is interested: https://github.com/vector-im/element-web/issues/21851 demonstrates the sort of mess you get into if you allow state events to be edited)

The current reading of the MSC looks good to me indeed!

A small oddity here.

```suggestion
longer receiving these edits; but showing slightly outdated text on a notification screen. That
is only a minor impact and it would be better to separate when (& why) we send pushes vs.
```

column14: Can the collector handle bundle info itself? Do we need to prefix with `gdpr_` on our page? `FormattableMarkup` please Can you not grab bundles off of `$definition`? That surprises me... Rather than duplicating the table code, you could do a count first and then inside the foreach handle the wrapper. Possibly swinging the other way from by previous comment about things in the collector, but should the collector be doing filtering? `FormattableMarkup` please Although this is how it's structured in D7, I'm wondering if we'd be better having the filename defined per bundle, rather than on relationships? It does limit you in that you can't have the same bundle put into different files depending on the relationships, but that has issues if the same entity is applicable via multiple relationships (it will only appear in one file which may not be obvious)... I think @jamieaa64 was suggesting we should actually go the other way and only explicitly include relationships. It's worse if we include data we shouldn't (i.e. data disclosure) than if miss data that should be included (i.e. incomplete fulfilment of SAR). Probably also worth trying to steer clear of double negatives as they just get confusing from both a UX and DX point of view. We could combine this and the above into a single relationship field. Correct. The changed version file is the trigger to create a new tag and release. So when doing a manual hotfix release, you can cherry-pick a commit or manually push a commit and only then change the VERSION file in an additional commit to trigger the build.

You can just pass a device_id on login and you get signed in as that device_id. Some bots do that, afaik, but afaik they usually don't use txn ids.

So, I haven't found how OIDC does that then, but how does the server then know, when to throw away encryption keys, if there are no client sessions you can terminate? And if there are such sessions, wouldn't it make more sense to link the txn id to a "session concept" instead of device ids, which can be reused?

There are two parts to this in the [OIDC proposal](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3861):

1. The client generates their own device ID and specifies it in the OIDC scope that is requested at the point of sign in. This scope described in [MSC2967](https://github.com/sandhose/matrix-doc/blob/msc/sandhose/api-scopes/proposals/2967-api-scopes.md#device-id-handling)
2. When the client signs out the OpenID Provider is responsible for informing the Homeserver that the device should be deleted. This process is described in [MSC2964](https://github.com/sandhose/matrix-doc/blob/msc/sandhose/oauth2-profile/proposals/2964-oauth2-profile.md#logging-out)

I'm somewhat struggling to follow this explanation. I think an example of how it might happen in practice is illustrative:

A device ID could have multiple sequences of access tokens associated
with it (since device ID can be specified as a parameter to 
[`/login`](https://spec.matrix.org/v1.6/client-server-api/#post_matrixclientv3login)). 

For example, a "bot" implementation might masquerade as the same "device" despite
calling `/login` on every run by passing the same device ID. Such a device might
also use the same transaction ID on each run.
```

 ```

        $dotenv = new Dotenv(false);

I think that these changes should be reverted. Read the last comment in https://www.php.net/manual/en/reserved.variables.environment.php#114811:

> Please note that writing to $_ENV does not actually set an environment variable, i.e. the variable will not propagate to any child processes you launch (except forked script processes, in which case it's just a variable in the script's memory). To set real environment variables, you must use putenv().

However, in https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.putenv.php the first comment states:

> putenv/getenv, $_ENV, and phpinfo(INFO_ENVIRONMENT) are three completely distinct environment stores. doing putenv("x=y") does not affect $_ENV; but also doing $_ENV["x"]="y" likewise does not affect getenv("x").

So I'm wondering whether we should just go with `new Dotenv(true);` to keep the current behavior.

I think that these changes should be reverted. Read the last comment in https://www.php.net/manual/en/reserved.variables.environment.php#114811:

> Please note that writing to $_ENV does not actually set an environment variable, i.e. the variable will not propagate to any child processes you launch (except forked script processes, in which case it's just a variable in the script's memory). To set real environment variables, you must use putenv().

However, in https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.putenv.php the first comment states:

> putenv/getenv, $_ENV, and phpinfo(INFO_ENVIRONMENT) are three completely distinct environment stores. doing putenv("x=y") does not affect $_ENV; but also doing $_ENV["x"]="y" likewise does not affect getenv("x").

So I'm wondering whether we should just go with `new Dotenv(true);` to keep the current behavior.

in theory, yes. And yes, synapse is non-compliant. The idea is that making a request without an `auth` property is a way to find out what authentication is required.

Could we mandate that clients hoping to take advantage of this exemption proactively supply an `m.login.dummy` auth dict?

Okay. I've made https://github.com/matrix-org/synapse/issues/15166 about the Synapse compliance. I don't think it needs to impact this MSC so I will update this section.

Also chances are the user has just entered their password on the registration form, so they'll likely remember it anyhow.

A possible security issue around this is accounts which are ancient (created more than an hour in the past) and under control of an attacker: they could use the user's existing non-encrypted reputation to potentially get people to trust a new master key. However, this is adequately covered by the "should" in the proposal - the homeserver can decide it's been too long and enact UIA.

Yes, there could indeed be scenarios where the homeserver admin wishes to implement some alternative logic depending on the account/user state or other policy.

This could be clarified in the actual spec changes such that a client should be prepared to complete UIA even if it is the first time keys are being uploaded.

I think we probably need to be more explicit about what, exactly, we mean by "not requiring UIA".

Should the client submit the request with no `auth` dict at all, changing the part of the spec that says

> A request to an endpoint that uses User-Interactive Authentication never succeeds without auth.

?

Or does the client make a request with an ` m.login.dummy` auth type?

I think this is unquestionably a good idea and is entirely sensible, but I'm also not sure you need an MSC for this? I think it depends on the 'should' in this sentence. If it were a 'must', clients could rely on any server claiming to support a recent enough version of the spec allowing this request without auth. If it's just a recommended behaviour, aren't servers free to just allow the request with no auth? (Although also rich's comment below about being more specific about no auth dict vs `m.login.dummy`). That said, an MSC to set intentions could still be useful, but there may be no need for this to block you.

It's hard to tell from the spec, but I think we do actually require an MSC to at least make the intention clear. What "should" actually equates to, as has been pointed out, is a question, though the actual behaviour of whether it's legal to return no flows, etc is undetermined at present. This MSC would codify that.

You are using a string to store the segments in `playedSegments`, so you should not intialize it with an empty array. However, since the variable should store uniform objects, I think using an array makes more sense and will e.g. remove the need to deconstruct the string and reconstruct it later in `endPlayedSegment` and `getProgress`. You have more flexibility this way. When you finally need the string for output, you can just join the array elements (in a separate function), but using an array for storing you could e.g. now easily filter for segments of particular length, sort them, etc. if that's needed later (you sort them in `getProgress`).

The same is true for each segment itself, which contains a startTime and an endTime. You could make the code easier by storing a segment as an object such as `{start: x, end: y}` (which would even describe what you're looking at) or as an array `[x, y]`. You will not have to constantly convert from strings to arrays or numbers and back. Instead, just turn the segment in the final string form of s.xxx[.]s.xxx  when you need it.

If missing, quality will be set to either the width or the height of the video. The video CoP isn't clear about this, but it seems to prefer the video height as an indicator of quality, e.g. 720, 1080.

It's not clear whether `width` and `height` are mandatory parameters, but since you compare `width` against being undefined, they might be considered optional or not necessarily set explicitly. In this case, `height` might be undefined or an empty string, possibly leading to something as "1920x" for the `playbackSize`.

`Document.fullscreen` is marked as obsolete, cmp. https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document/fullscreen. The variable state might be renamed to `fullscreen` or `isFullscreen`.

`secondsTiISO8601Duration` does not work as intended. It doesn't return a string defined by the ISO8601 standard. The unit specific segments are returned as absolute totals, not as the "remainders".

For example, the input value of 8192 (seconds) should return PT2H16M32S for 2 hours, 16 minutes and 32 seconds, but it returns PT2H136M8192S.

As mentioned in the previews review comments, there's the same pattern in all the previous functions and they are identical to a large degree. One way to make the code more compact would be to use something to wrap it all like

    /**
     * Generates 'seeked' xAPI statement (Video Profile).

     * @param {number} currentTime - Time of the video currently.
     * @param {Object} params - Parameters.
     * @param {string} params.verb - Verb for the xAPI statement.
     * @param {Object} [params.result] - Extensions for the object.
     * @param {Object} [params.extensionsContext] - Extensions for the context.
     * @return {Object} JSON xAPI statement
     */
    self.getArgsXAPI = function (currentTime, params) {
      params.extensionsObject = params.extensionsObject || {};
      params.extensionsContext = params.extensionsContext || {};

      var dateTime = new Date();
      var timeStamp = dateTime.toISOString();

      return {
        'verb': {
          'id': 'http://adlnet.gov/expapi/verbs/' + params.verb,
          'display': {'en-US': params.verb}
        },
        'object': getXAPIObject(),
        'result': params.result,
        'context': {
          'contextActivities': {'category': [{'id': 'https://w3id.org/xapi/video'}]},
          'extensions': params.extensionsContext
        },
        'timestamp' : timeStamp
      };
    };

and then the individual trigger functions could remain something like

    self.getArgsXAPIPlayed = function (currentTime) {
      var resultExtTime = formatFloat(currentTime);
      playingSegmentStart = resultExtTime;

      return self.getArgsXAPI(currentTime, {
        verb: 'played',
        result: {extensions: {'https://w3id.org/xapi/video/extensions/time': resultExtTime}},
        extensionsObject: {'https://w3id.org/xapi/video/extensions/session-id': sessionID}
      });
    };

Alternatively, you could also work with several smaller functions that add a particular field's contents like it has been done in some other occasions with xAPI. For example something that works like:
    xapiEvent.setExtensions(context, {'full-screen': isFullscreen', 'screen-size': screenSize});

I was getting this randomly in my testing, too (progress getting close to 1.0, but not quite reaching it). I noticed when repeatedly pausing/playing the video, the recorded end time when pausing and the recorded start time when playing would be a few milliseconds apart.

Example `playedSegments` where I paused an 8-second video twice, once around the 3 second mark, and once around the 5 second mark:

We've talked at length about what "completing" a video means, and I'm pretty sure it's not "watched every last millisecond of the video." But it's hard to pin down (what if a video rolls credits for a couple minutes at the end, can you skip that? What if a student skips a few seconds of a repetitive part in the middle of the video?).

For our purposes, I would be ok with allowing some delta away from 100% that would still be considered "complete"; we could say `if (progress >= 0.95)`, or maybe define a class constant for some delta value, and then say `if (progress >= 1 - delta)`. Thoughts?

I can expand on this a bit. The video profile CoP agrees that there are use cases (technical or otherwise) that would require complete to trigger on a progress value < 1.0. 

We have a profile solution for this that we are finalizing. It requires adding an extension in the initialized statement that defines the minimum progress value used by the Activity Provider (H5P in this case) to trigger the completed statement. As long as this value exists then analysis can still be implement across data sets with different minimum values.

Short term solution is hard code `if (progress >= 0.95)`, but we would ideally prefer a UI element to set the delta. You will also need to change the other `subject_own` and `subject_other` translations further down this file - there are separate subjects for "commented" "closed" and "reopened" events.

Unfortunately, for technical reasons explained below, you can't change the interpolation variables in a translation, without also changing the key.

The technical reason is that the interpolation variables must be exactly the same in all translations for the same key. It can take several weeks, or longer, for all the translators to update their translations, and in the meantime the code would not work in those languages. So if you change the interpolations in a value, you need to change the key (e.g. `subject_own`) to something else too.

I would maybe remove this test and use a default value in `setCookie` like before.
This way any falsy or 0 value would be set to the default.
```
setCookie(
	this.cookieName,
	value,
	cookieExpiresAfterDays || 120,
	this.config.cookieDomain
);
```

`cookieExpiresAfterDays` could then be a `const` var.

This is not related to the code but I'm mentioning it here so it is in the review : 
could you update the README to document this feature?

I agree with falsies values but `0` as an integer has a meaning for cookie expiration which ends when browser is closed. Using `cookieExpiresAfterDays || 120` will replace `0` to `120` which may not be the expected behavior by the end developer.

To not break existing installations, the default could apply to non-functional `cookieExpiresAfterDays` (like before this feature). When used as a function it'll be up to the developer to explicitly return a value if he don't want a session cookie.

Sure! Documented here: https://github.com/empreinte-digitale/orejime/pull/79/commits/e0270778dccf26f050938e30dd5685669f07c3f4

I didn't know about this behavior with 0, given the old implementation I thought it was kind of invalid.
I'm kind of torn here, it would be a breaking change to modify the current behavior, but it seems odd to have different behaviors for different methods...

column14:
It doesn't look like we have a consistent way to name this type of variable for the azure provider.  In AWS it's most commonly `annotation_key`, but in Azure I see a pretty even mix of `cache_key`, `annotation_key` and `<attribute>_key`, and `<attribute>_property`. It's probably worth converging on (and documenting) an Azure convention going forward.

`cache_key` seems clear enough in this context, though I can also see that causing confusion with the cache_key used [with the local disk cache](https://github.com/cloud-custodian/cloud-custodian/blob/df9b68f8e9309254ff2b70735e2ec195010e1ba8/tools/c7n_azure/c7n_azure/query.py#L265-L282).

I like this clear/explicit handling of the previous behavior :+1: 

I know this is closed now, but the idea of annotations is something that I don't fully understand. My assumption has been that it is meant as an addition to the resource data that would show up in the final output for a matched resource. However, I'm not aware of any documentation around their use, and the confusing part is that the annotation also tends to end up being a local cache for filter data which is separate from the more generic cache you mention.

All that to say I agree there should be a standard for handling what is a pretty common pattern across filters.

Yes, it is intended this way, so that the home page is never empty. If the user decides to unsubscribe from all their movements, the tutorial just comes back, which will redirect to the movements page if finished.

The app-'something' is the name of the component selector, so that this page appears here. For all pages, the selector starts with app, e.g. app-add-movement, or app-home. So I stuck to this convention also for the tutorial page.

The idea is that if the tutorial appears on the home page, this is because the user is not subscribed to any movements, so the tutorial fills the home page. The user can always navigate away from the homepage if they want, but the idea is that the user finishes the tutorial and is then navigated to the movements page. If the user opens the tutorial from the about page, this can also happen by accident (selected the wrong button), or because they just want to get a quick look. So for those cases, I put the close button in the corner for easy dismissal.

One thing we can do to help our routes file from getting too large is to consider making multiple files containing routes separated by the resource type. We might have a `routes` folder instead of a `routes.py` file, and inside that folder (along with a `__init__.py`) we could have a file per resource, so `task.py` and `goal.py`. Where each would have a blueprint and endpoints for that resource. When we have one blueprint per file, we often name the blueprint simply `bp` rather  than including the resource name as part of it.

Then here, we could import and register the blueprints like
```python
    from .routes import task, goal
    app.register_blueprint(task.bp)
    app.register_blueprint(goal.bp)
```

One thing to be careful of is what we should always try to return consistent result type from methods, so if one path returns a list of results, we should generally try to return lists (even if they are empty do to no results)  fo consistency. This can help the function caller write simpler code. Currently, if `title_from_url` is falsy, this function falls through and would return `None`. Returning `None` can be ok (though we should generally do it explicitly, otherwise it can look like we simply forgot to think about that case), but if we returned an empty list, then the caller could always simply iterate over any (possible no) results safely. According to the SqlAlchemy docs about [autoincrement](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/14/core/metadata.html#sqlalchemy.schema.Column.params.autoincrement):

> The default value is the string "auto" which indicates that a single-column primary key that is of an INTEGER type with no stated client-side or python-side defaults should receive auto increment semantics automatically; all other varieties of primary key columns will not.

This means that here, since the primary is not a compound key, the type is integer, and there's no specified default value, the desired autoincrement behavior will apply even without listing it. It wouldn't hurt anything to list it, but it's not required.


It turns out that `nullable=True` is the default value for nullable. So all of the columns for Task here are currently impicitly marked as nullable. But should title or description be allowed to be NULL? (Does that make sense from a data standpoint?) Consider adding `nullable=False` to those columns.

The way the project emphasized that completed_at needs to accept NULL values may make it seem like we needed to explicitly call out that nullable should be True, but it turns out this is the default for nullable. Instead, we should think about the other data in our model and consider whether it makes sense for any of it to be NULL. If not, we can have the database help us protect against that happening!

Notice that this chunk of looking up an id, checking for None, and returning a 404 when not found recurs frequently. It's a little tricky to extract this into a helper function, mostly since a helper function can't force the calling function to exit. That is, unless it raises an error. So we could think about writing a helper function to perform this set of steps, but we would also need to customize the Flask error handling behavior to return JSON rather than HTML. There _is_ the `get_or_404` method that essentially does the lookup with errors already, but we would should still update the flask error handling (see [here](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/2.0.x/errorhandling/#error-handlers) for more details.)

Another approach could be to use a decorator to intercept the task id from the route, and performt the lookup before reaching the body of our endpoint. There's an example of that [here](https://github.com/AdaGold/hello-books-api-decorated/blob/main/app/routes.py).


We should be sure that the same fields required for POSTing are included here for PUT. PUT _replaces_ the value for the supplied task id, so we should ensure that all of the values required to represent a `Task` are provided with the same restrictions as we had when creating it in the first place.

Having this around could confuse flask, since both this and the other migration look like "first" migrations (neither has a non-None `down_revision` value, which is how flask traces back the migration dependencies). So flask could theoretically pick either as the first, and you could end up with weird situations where a deployment won't properly generate the tables on the remote server, even if it's working locally.

Try to keep an eye out for stray migrations and keep them tidy.

I would probably prefer to use a data-mx-pack-url parameter on the img tag. That way only clients, that support custom emoji would render it as a link and they can know, that this is intended to share a custom emoji set. Otherwise users clicking the link might be confused and you can't really use emoji inside of link descriptions anymore.

You probably want to specify some prefix for the pack_url field, so that you don't reserve the name, while this MSC is still unmerged. It would add some more overhead to each event, but I think it is nicer for the ecosystem to namespace independent MSCs. :)

(Once that exists, I would probably start implementing it)

I think I would prefer this to be a bit more lenient. A user should be able to disable this, but also I would like it, if a client is allowed to share a link to a pack, as long as every recipient would be able to access the pack. For example in a closed community, if there is a room with sticker packs, that any of the community members could join using "restricted joins" or "knocking", then sharing a link to the pack would still be nice. For invite only rooms it of course never makes sense.

What's the use case for having this work outside of Matrix clients?

The links should be sharable outside of Matrix, such as over other social media.  This can allow users to post lists and collections of image packs on those platforms.

I'll update the doc to say that links should be sharable outside of Matrix clients - the link itself will still lead to opening Matrix.

That means I should be able to share a link outside matrix, but I don't need the embedding in the message to be accessible outside matrix, right? I.e. it doesn't need to be a link embedded into the img tag for that to work, but a data attribute fulfills that in the same way, since the attribute would still be a matrix.to link?

This means you probably want to add some metadata to the matrix.to link, so that it can be distinguished from a normal event link, I guess? I.e. appending a ?image_pack or so?

I figure that for closed communities, the community organizers already have a way to distribute their image packs to their members, so the utility is a little bit less.  The hope of this MSC is to allow public image packs to "go viral" and spread far beyond their original source.

Still, it makes sense that it doesn't hurt to allow these links.  In this case, I will leave it open as an optional feature.

Right, basically I just mean we want a matrix.to link, rather than some bespoke link that can only be clicked within a matrix client.  We don't need to expose any new data to the outside world.



Adding a query param won't automatically be passed through matrix.to to the matrix client.  This might be a useful expansion, but it adds a lot of complexity and I think it's functional as-is.

The person sharing the matrix.to link should be responsible for describing what it is - already a matrix.to event link doesn't give the room name or any other info, so sharers already have to do this.

You probably want clients as well as intermediates (like the matrix.to page) to know what the link is for before or without resolving it to the actual event. Otherwise matrix.to will just show "you were invited to room X". You probably want to be able to show, that you were linked to a sticker pack instead, which needs additional metadata in the link. Similarly you probably want clients to suggest you to add the sticker pack instead of scrolling to the event. This means again, you want extra metadata. In general such parameters are passed to clients, that can handle matrix.to, but possibly it would need to be supported by the matrix: scheme as well.

You don't really want clients to have to do some deep inspection of every matrix.to target to be able to use it and you don't want to have users paste the link into some field, but in the best case have it be automatic when clicking a link, that the client does the right thing. It is less complex to just add metadata to the matrix.to link than have every client do deep inspection of the link target before prompting the user what to do. That is why matrix.to already distinguishes between room, user and event links and why the matrix URI format has a specific action parameter, describing the purpose of a link. This is handled before any request is sent to a server, so that the user can decide what to do.

Hmmm, action= seems like the right thing to do here.  Unfortunately, matrix.to and also Element don't honor this value.  You can see here that https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix.to/blob/main/src/open/clients/Nheko.js#L49 that action is harcoded depending on the resource type.  I think the only query params that work here are the ones on the matrix.to homepage.  Matrix.to always shows the same prompt "choose app to continue" regardless of the room type.

I think adding an additional metadata to the url does make sense, but it needs a bunch of additional things to move at the same time.  I'll document a bit more about what is wanted here though.

You can just add an unrecognized action. Clients that want to use that metadata can then do that, but if they don't recognize it, they should just ignore it and handle it like normal events, which I would say is fine :)

Hi @nisarhassan12! As suggested in our 1:1 discussion, please look into:
- [ ] How to write high-performance scroll event listeners (i.e. they should never block scrolling, and they should never be a performance problem -- I remember seeing various blog posts about how to do this from people in the front-end community, but I don't have a direct link)
- [ ] How to debounce things that happen too frequently (e.g. if this listener happens 1000 times per second, maybe you can debounce it such that it only happens a few times per second)

Additionally, I took a look at why the edge dots are sometimes not selected (last dot on desktop, first on mobile).

The value `element.scrollLeft` actually goes from `0` to `element.scrollWidth - element.clientWidth` (taking `clientWidth` into account is important). So:
- When `scrollLeft` is `0`, the left-most dot should be highlighted
- When `scrollLeft` is `scrollWidth - clientWidth`, the right-most dot should be highlighted
- When it's in-between, maybe you can divide the percentage by `scrollBy`, but first you'll need to verify that `scrollBy * cycles` is the same as `scrollWidth`

Hope this helps! Let me know if you still run into problems with this (then maybe we could finish solving it together in a call).

There is no need to use `axios` since we are polyfilling the `fetch()` API.

I've some suggestions:

1. Check if GDPR protection is enabled and the user has approved its data collection;
2. Use the own browser's geolocation API before using an external service;
3. If the geolocation API fails, request to `geoip-db.com` as a fallback;
4. Verify the limits for commercial use off `geoip-db.com` -- despite Rocket.Chat and this client being MIT; 
5. The `fetch()` API has some options to properly do CORS requests;
6. The ipify functionally can be implemented on Rocket.Chat's Livechat API, decreasing the number of requests needed.

try to change it to 

if (bio == NULL)

to pass codacy.

Long time no see Daniel ;)

> @rgerhards , @alorbach , is there any trick to make Codacy happy with respect to the "unknown" SO_BINDTODEVICE value?

I think this issue is a false positive and can be ignored. 
I have commented above on the other issue. 

Indeed, pretty long time :)

Pushed a bio==NULL variant.

Let's see if that passes codacy.


Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

I guess a knob to turn of all certificate revocation checks off would probably be helpful, to mimic the previous behavior. Personally I would prefer if (online) revocation checks would be done by default, which might be expected by some TLS users.

I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

No luck with codacy:

   `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

> No luck with codacy:
> 
> `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

@rgerhards do you see the reason why this is detected as issue? 

> Indeed, pretty long time :)
> 
> Pushed a bio==NULL variant.
> 
> Let's see if that passes codacy.
> 
> Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

Yes indeed I would recommend to have configuration options in imtcp and omfwd enabling  / disabling OCSP checking with default OFF to maintain existing behavior. 
With a name like "StreamDriver.TlsVerifyOcsp" (See other TLS Options in imtcp/omfwd doc): 
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/imtcp.html
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/omfwd.html

You needs some additional coding to pass the configuration option from the module down to the nsd driver. And also "not implented" wrappers in nsd_gtls and nsd_ptcp drivers. Here is an older PR where I added "streamdriver.permitexpiredcerts" which you can use a template: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/pull/3366

> I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.

Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service? 

> > Indeed, pretty long time :)
> > Pushed a bio==NULL variant.
> > Let's see if that passes codacy.
> > Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

> With a name like "StreamDriver.TlsVerifyOcsp" (See other TLS Options in imtcp/omfwd doc):
> https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/imtcp.html
> https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/omfwd.html
>
