> #3366


Ok, I'll look into introduce those knobs.

With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the  end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 /  https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
(which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )


I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the  end-entity or in the certificate path:

```
$ openssl s_client -connect github.com:443 < /dev/null 2> /dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout | grep -A5 -E '(Authority Information Access|CRL Distribution Points)'
            X509v3 CRL Distribution Points: 

                Full Name:
                  URI:http://crl3.digicert.com/sha2-ha-server-g6.crl

                Full Name:
--
            Authority Information Access: 
                OCSP - URI:http://ocsp.digicert.com
                CA Issuers - URI:http://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertSHA2HighAssuranceServerCA.crt

            X509v3 Basic Constraints: critical
                CA:FALSE
```

This would not affect existing deployment using private PKI environment without any CRL/OCSP URL in the issued certificate.

Not sure if "ignoring" OCSP/CRL URLs as part of certificate validation would be categorized as https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/299.html

(Yes, the browsers don't do by default live online reovcation either IIUC, but they have some sort of regular caches updated transparently to the user. So there is at least some revocation checking going on)

On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server. Maybe something worth to look into to add for rsyslog in future.

> 
> > I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.
> 
> For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.
> 
> Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service?

Sure, first you need to issue a set of certificates with a OCSP URI (Authority Information Access) included. To generate such testing purposes I build this: https://github.com/danos/vyatta-security-vpn/tree/master/docs/x509

I'll look into the existing rsyslog UTs if I can enhance/add something to existing ossl related UTs.

For development I used openssl as OCSP responder/server:
```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10
```

The index.txt is the file which openssl generates when you use OpenSSL to build a PKI. In this example the certificate for server13 got revoked. And `openssl ocsp -index indext.txt` basically uses that file as revocation database.

```
$ cat index.txt
V       191110011802Z           00      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=client1/emailAddress=client1+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
R       191110011822Z   181110011831Z   02      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=server13/emailAddress=server13+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
```

To make use of OCSP nonces add `-nonce`:

```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10 -nonce
```


I haven't checked other free/open implementations yet. FreeIPA/dogtag PKI might be worth a look. But for self-contained UTs `openssl ocsp` might be sufficient I guess.

The only other detailed behavior change between different production OCSP responder/server deployments, which are easy to overlook if you just use `openssl ocsp`: the HTTP requests need to hold a "Host" header entry. Most or many public CA vendor seem to use CDN providers to guarantee their OCSP availability and responsiveness.

> With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 / https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
> (which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )
> 
> I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the end-entity or in the certificate path:

Thanks for the details, @rgerhards I think under these circumstances it is save and reasonable to have OCSP checking enabled by default with the possibility to disable it if needed.

> On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server.

> V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com

That would be fully sufficient as ocsp server to build a testcase on. 
It just needs to be started in background and killed on shutdown. 
This needs some additional plumbing in diag.sh like done for this test here:
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_omsnmpv1_udp.sh
(See snmp_start_trapreceiver  and snmp_stop_trapreceiver )

If you create sample ca / certifcates based on your script, but make them last longer (Like 36500 days) which is ok for the testbench, add them to here for example (tests/testsuites/x.509), you can use these tests as template to build your own test on: 

https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_tls_certvalid.sh
(Just replace '$RS_TLS_DRIVER' with ossl, as this will only run for openssl). 
And this tests: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/imtcp-tls-ossl-basic.sh

You can run single tests manually when you build rsyslog like this:
- go to rsyslog source dir
- export srcdir=./
- autoreconf -vfi 
- ./configure ... your options ...
- make && make check 
- ...wait until first tests runs then break with CTRL + C
- cd tests
- ./yourtestcase.sh

Can this check be moved into a helper function? I see that it's being checked more than 15 times the same thing, and I believe it would be better to move this into a separate function to reduce future maintenance.

`export const useRealName = (uid?: string) => getMessagesLayoutPreference(uid) !== 'username'`

This one is also interesting to move into a helper function, it's the same code being used 9 times along the app.

_note: Might need to think on a different name for this function, or rename the other I suggested_
```
export const useRealName = () => {
	const messagesLayoutPreference = useUserPreference('messagesLayout');
	const defaultMessagesLayout = useSetting('Accounts_Default_User_Preferences_messagesLayout');
	return messagesLayoutPreference !== 'default' ? messagesLayoutPreference !== 'username' : defaultMessagesLayout !== 'username';
}
```

Fixed! I had to change the way `useUserPreference` works so that it never returns the string `default`.

Fixed!

I don't think this is a good Idea. We can have users without names, and this could be really bad for those users 🙈 

I think you forgot to readd this check

Let's just reset this file so it has no changes

I think we should only use the default value of the preference in the backend if we get it from the user. Otherwise we use the old setting.

Same comment here. Prefer setting over default preference.

Let's change this to optional chaining.

Long time no see Daniel ;)

> @rgerhards , @alorbach , is there any trick to make Codacy happy with respect to the "unknown" SO_BINDTODEVICE value?

I think this issue is a false positive and can be ignored. 
I have commented above on the other issue. 

Indeed, pretty long time :)

Pushed a bio==NULL variant.

Let's see if that passes codacy.


Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

I guess a knob to turn of all certificate revocation checks off would probably be helpful, to mimic the previous behavior. Personally I would prefer if (online) revocation checks would be done by default, which might be expected by some TLS users.

I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

No luck with codacy:

   `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

> No luck with codacy:
> 
> `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

@rgerhards do you see the reason why this is detected as issue? 

> Indeed, pretty long time :)
> 
> Pushed a bio==NULL variant.
> 
> Let's see if that passes codacy.
> 
> Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

Yes indeed I would recommend to have configuration options in imtcp and omfwd enabling  / disabling OCSP checking with default OFF to maintain existing behavior. 
With a name like "StreamDriver.TlsVerifyOcsp" (See other TLS Options in imtcp/omfwd doc): 
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/imtcp.html
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/omfwd.html

You needs some additional coding to pass the configuration option from the module down to the nsd driver. And also "not implented" wrappers in nsd_gtls and nsd_ptcp drivers. Here is an older PR where I added "streamdriver.permitexpiredcerts" which you can use a template: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/pull/3366

> I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.

Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service?

> #3366


Ok, I'll look into introduce those knobs.

With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the  end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 /  https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
(which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )


I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the  end-entity or in the certificate path:

```
$ openssl s_client -connect github.com:443 < /dev/null 2> /dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout | grep -A5 -E '(Authority Information Access|CRL Distribution Points)'
            X509v3 CRL Distribution Points: 

                Full Name:
                  URI:http://crl3.digicert.com/sha2-ha-server-g6.crl

                Full Name:
--
            Authority Information Access: 
                OCSP - URI:http://ocsp.digicert.com
                CA Issuers - URI:http://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertSHA2HighAssuranceServerCA.crt

            X509v3 Basic Constraints: critical
                CA:FALSE
```

This would not affect existing deployment using private PKI environment without any CRL/OCSP URL in the issued certificate.

Not sure if "ignoring" OCSP/CRL URLs as part of certificate validation would be categorized as https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/299.html

(Yes, the browsers don't do by default live online reovcation either IIUC, but they have some sort of regular caches updated transparently to the user. So there is at least some revocation checking going on)

On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server. Maybe something worth to look into to add for rsyslog in future.

> 
> > I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.
> 
> For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.
> 
> Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service?

Sure, first you need to issue a set of certificates with a OCSP URI (Authority Information Access) included. To generate such testing purposes I build this: https://github.com/danos/vyatta-security-vpn/tree/master/docs/x509

I'll look into the existing rsyslog UTs if I can enhance/add something to existing ossl related UTs.

For development I used openssl as OCSP responder/server:
```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10
```

The index.txt is the file which openssl generates when you use OpenSSL to build a PKI. In this example the certificate for server13 got revoked. And `openssl ocsp -index indext.txt` basically uses that file as revocation database.

```
$ cat index.txt
V       191110011802Z           00      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=client1/emailAddress=client1+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
R       191110011822Z   181110011831Z   02      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=server13/emailAddress=server13+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
```

To make use of OCSP nonces add `-nonce`:

```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10 -nonce
```


I haven't checked other free/open implementations yet. FreeIPA/dogtag PKI might be worth a look. But for self-contained UTs `openssl ocsp` might be sufficient I guess.

The only other detailed behavior change between different production OCSP responder/server deployments, which are easy to overlook if you just use `openssl ocsp`: the HTTP requests need to hold a "Host" header entry. Most or many public CA vendor seem to use CDN providers to guarantee their OCSP availability and responsiveness.

That would be fully sufficient as ocsp server to build a testcase on. 
It just needs to be started in background and killed on shutdown. 
This needs some additional plumbing in diag.sh like done for this test here:
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_omsnmpv1_udp.sh
(See snmp_start_trapreceiver  and snmp_stop_trapreceiver )

If you create sample ca / certifcates based on your script, but make them last longer (Like 36500 days) which is ok for the testbench, add them to here for example (tests/testsuites/x.509), you can use these tests as template to build your own test on: 

https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_tls_certvalid.sh
(Just replace '$RS_TLS_DRIVER' with ossl, as this will only run for openssl). 
And this tests: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/imtcp-tls-ossl-basic.sh

You can run single tests manually when you build rsyslog like this:
- go to rsyslog source dir
- export srcdir=./
- autoreconf -vfi 
- ./configure ... your options ...
- make && make check 
- ...wait until first tests runs then break with CTRL + C
- cd tests
- ./yourtestcase.sh

if (bio == NULL)

to pass codacy.

Long time no see Daniel ;)

> @rgerhards , @alorbach , is there any trick to make Codacy happy with respect to the "unknown" SO_BINDTODEVICE value?

I think this issue is a false positive and can be ignored. 
I have commented above on the other issue. 

Indeed, pretty long time :)

Pushed a bio==NULL variant.

Let's see if that passes codacy.


Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

I guess a knob to turn of all certificate revocation checks off would probably be helpful, to mimic the previous behavior. Personally I would prefer if (online) revocation checks would be done by default, which might be expected by some TLS users.

I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

No luck with codacy:

   `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

> No luck with codacy:
> 
> `Condition 'bio==NULL' is always false`

@rgerhards do you see the reason why this is detected as issue? 

> Indeed, pretty long time :)
> 
> Pushed a bio==NULL variant.
> 
> Let's see if that passes codacy.
> 
> Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?

Yes indeed I would recommend to have configuration options in imtcp and omfwd enabling  / disabling OCSP checking with default OFF to maintain existing behavior. 
With a name like "StreamDriver.TlsVerifyOcsp" (See other TLS Options in imtcp/omfwd doc): 
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/imtcp.html
https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/omfwd.html

You needs some additional coding to pass the configuration option from the module down to the nsd driver. And also "not implented" wrappers in nsd_gtls and nsd_ptcp drivers. Here is an older PR where I added "streamdriver.permitexpiredcerts" which you can use a template: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/pull/3366

> I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.

For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.

Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service? 

> > Indeed, pretty long time :)
> > Pushed a bio==NULL variant.
> > Let's see if that passes codacy.
> > Do you have any preference or suggestion on additional configuration knobs?
> 
> Yes indeed I would recommend to have configuration options in imtcp and omfwd enabling / disabling OCSP checking with default OFF to maintain existing behavior.
> With a name like "StreamDriver.TlsVerifyOcsp" (See other TLS Options in imtcp/omfwd doc):
> https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/imtcp.html
> https://www.rsyslog.com/doc/master/configuration/modules/omfwd.html
> 
> You needs some additional coding to pass the configuration option from the module down to the nsd driver. And also "not implented" wrappers in nsd_gtls and nsd_ptcp drivers. Here is an older PR where I added "streamdriver.permitexpiredcerts" which you can use a template:
> #3366


Ok, I'll look into introduce those knobs.

With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the  end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 /  https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
(which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )


I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the  end-entity or in the certificate path:

```
$ openssl s_client -connect github.com:443 < /dev/null 2> /dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout | grep -A5 -E '(Authority Information Access|CRL Distribution Points)'
            X509v3 CRL Distribution Points: 

                Full Name:
                  URI:http://crl3.digicert.com/sha2-ha-server-g6.crl

                Full Name:
--
            Authority Information Access: 
                OCSP - URI:http://ocsp.digicert.com
                CA Issuers - URI:http://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertSHA2HighAssuranceServerCA.crt

            X509v3 Basic Constraints: critical
                CA:FALSE
```

This would not affect existing deployment using private PKI environment without any CRL/OCSP URL in the issued certificate.

Not sure if "ignoring" OCSP/CRL URLs as part of certificate validation would be categorized as https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/299.html

(Yes, the browsers don't do by default live online reovcation either IIUC, but they have some sort of regular caches updated transparently to the user. So there is at least some revocation checking going on)

On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server. Maybe something worth to look into to add for rsyslog in future.

> 
> > I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.
> 
> For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.
> 
> Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service?

Sure, first you need to issue a set of certificates with a OCSP URI (Authority Information Access) included. To generate such testing purposes I build this: https://github.com/danos/vyatta-security-vpn/tree/master/docs/x509

I'll look into the existing rsyslog UTs if I can enhance/add something to existing ossl related UTs.

For development I used openssl as OCSP responder/server:
```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10
```

The index.txt is the file which openssl generates when you use OpenSSL to build a PKI. In this example the certificate for server13 got revoked. And `openssl ocsp -index indext.txt` basically uses that file as revocation database.

```
$ cat index.txt
V       191110011802Z           00      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=client1/emailAddress=client1+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
R       191110011822Z   181110011831Z   02      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=server13/emailAddress=server13+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
```

To make use of OCSP nonces add `-nonce`:

```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10 -nonce
```


I haven't checked other free/open implementations yet. FreeIPA/dogtag PKI might be worth a look. But for self-contained UTs `openssl ocsp` might be sufficient I guess.

The only other detailed behavior change between different production OCSP responder/server deployments, which are easy to overlook if you just use `openssl ocsp`: the HTTP requests need to hold a "Host" header entry. Most or many public CA vendor seem to use CDN providers to guarantee their OCSP availability and responsiveness.

> With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 / https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
> (which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )
> 
> I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the end-entity or in the certificate path:

Thanks for the details, @rgerhards I think under these circumstances it is save and reasonable to have OCSP checking enabled by default with the possibility to disable it if needed.

> On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server.

Probably not yet ;).

That would be fully sufficient as ocsp server to build a testcase on. 
It just needs to be started in background and killed on shutdown. 
This needs some additional plumbing in diag.sh like done for this test here:
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_omsnmpv1_udp.sh
(See snmp_start_trapreceiver  and snmp_stop_trapreceiver )

If you create sample ca / certifcates based on your script, but make them last longer (Like 36500 days) which is ok for the testbench, add them to here for example (tests/testsuites/x.509), you can use these tests as template to build your own test on: 

https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_tls_certvalid.sh
(Just replace '$RS_TLS_DRIVER' with ossl, as this will only run for openssl). 
And this tests: 
https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/imtcp-tls-ossl-basic.sh

You can run single tests manually when you build rsyslog like this:
- go to rsyslog source dir
- export srcdir=./
- autoreconf -vfi 
- ./configure ... your options ...
- make && make check 
- ...wait until first tests runs then break with CTRL + C
- cd tests
- ./yourtestcase.sh

With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the  end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 /  https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
(which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )


I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the  end-entity or in the certificate path:

```
$ openssl s_client -connect github.com:443 < /dev/null 2> /dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout | grep -A5 -E '(Authority Information Access|CRL Distribution Points)'
            X509v3 CRL Distribution Points: 

                Full Name:
                  URI:http://crl3.digicert.com/sha2-ha-server-g6.crl

                Full Name:
--
            Authority Information Access: 
                OCSP - URI:http://ocsp.digicert.com
                CA Issuers - URI:http://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertSHA2HighAssuranceServerCA.crt

            X509v3 Basic Constraints: critical
                CA:FALSE
```

This would not affect existing deployment using private PKI environment without any CRL/OCSP URL in the issued certificate.

Not sure if "ignoring" OCSP/CRL URLs as part of certificate validation would be categorized as https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/299.html

(Yes, the browsers don't do by default live online reovcation either IIUC, but they have some sort of regular caches updated transparently to the user. So there is at least some revocation checking going on)

I'll look into the existing rsyslog UTs if I can enhance/add something to existing ossl related UTs.

For development I used openssl as OCSP responder/server:
```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10
```

The index.txt is the file which openssl generates when you use OpenSSL to build a PKI. In this example the certificate for server13 got revoked. And `openssl ocsp -index indext.txt` basically uses that file as revocation database.

```
$ cat index.txt
V       191110011802Z           00      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=client1/emailAddress=client1+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
R       191110011822Z   181110011831Z   02      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=server13/emailAddress=server13+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
```

To make use of OCSP nonces add `-nonce`:

```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10 -nonce
```


I haven't checked other free/open implementations yet. FreeIPA/dogtag PKI might be worth a look. But for self-contained UTs `openssl ocsp` might be sufficient I guess.

The only other detailed behavior change between different production OCSP responder/server deployments, which are easy to overlook if you just use `openssl ocsp`: the HTTP requests need to hold a "Host" header entry. Most or many public CA vendor seem to use CDN providers to guarantee their OCSP availability and responsiveness.

E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the  end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. At least that would be my naive expectation that TLS client comply with: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6 /  https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5280#section-6.3
(which is referred by https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5425#section-4.2.1 )


I understand that this might break existing deployments under certain circumstances. But on the long run I would encourage to perform online revocation checks if OCSP (or CRL) URL are embedded in the  end-entity or in the certificate path:

```
$ openssl s_client -connect github.com:443 < /dev/null 2> /dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout | grep -A5 -E '(Authority Information Access|CRL Distribution Points)'
            X509v3 CRL Distribution Points: 

                Full Name:
                  URI:http://crl3.digicert.com/sha2-ha-server-g6.crl

                Full Name:
--
            Authority Information Access: 
                OCSP - URI:http://ocsp.digicert.com
                CA Issuers - URI:http://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertSHA2HighAssuranceServerCA.crt

            X509v3 Basic Constraints: critical
                CA:FALSE
```

This would not affect existing deployment using private PKI environment without any CRL/OCSP URL in the issued certificate.

Not sure if "ignoring" OCSP/CRL URLs as part of certificate validation would be categorized as https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/299.html

(Yes, the browsers don't do by default live online reovcation either IIUC, but they have some sort of regular caches updated transparently to the user. So there is at least some revocation checking going on)

On the long run OCSP stapling support would be obviously nice. The initial motivation for us implementing this was fulfilling some security requirements as syslog+TLS client, not as server. Not sure if there is on the market already a OCSP stapling aware syslog server. Maybe something worth to look into to add for rsyslog in future.

> 
> > I could contribute online CRL support as well, but that is rather complex, with delta-CRLs and such things. And not sure if online CRLs has really a future. Most or all public CAs do OCSP today, might be also a CAB Forum requirement (haven't checked). Letsencrypt does OCSP-only. So I wonder if online CRL is worth the burden.
> 
> For now I would also recommend too leave it with OCSP for now. If CRL becomes more important in future, it can be discussed again.
> 
> Btw., it would be great if we could get a testcase for OCSP. Do you have an idea how to do make one that works with a free and reliable OCSP service?

Sure, first you need to issue a set of certificates with a OCSP URI (Authority Information Access) included. To generate such testing purposes I build this: https://github.com/danos/vyatta-security-vpn/tree/master/docs/x509

I'll look into the existing rsyslog UTs if I can enhance/add something to existing ossl related UTs.

For development I used openssl as OCSP responder/server:
```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10
```

The index.txt is the file which openssl generates when you use OpenSSL to build a PKI. In this example the certificate for server13 got revoked. And `openssl ocsp -index indext.txt` basically uses that file as revocation database.

```
$ cat index.txt
V       191110011802Z           00      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=client1/emailAddress=client1+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
V       191110011816Z           01      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=serverA/emailAddress=serverA+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
R       191110011822Z   181110011831Z   02      unknown /C=US/ST=CA/O=AT&T/OU=Labs/CN=server13/emailAddress=server13+rsa@vyatta.att-mail.com
```

To make use of OCSP nonces add `-nonce`:

```
openssl ocsp -index index.txt -port 8888 -rsigner RSA_ocsp1.pem -rkey RSA_ocsp1.key -CA RSA_CA.pem -text -nmin 10 -nonce
```


I haven't checked other free/open implementations yet. FreeIPA/dogtag PKI might be worth a look. But for self-contained UTs `openssl ocsp` might be sufficient I guess.

The only other detailed behavior change between different production OCSP responder/server deployments, which are easy to overlook if you just use `openssl ocsp`: the HTTP requests need to hold a "Host" header entry. Most or many public CA vendor seem to use CDN providers to guarantee their OCSP availability and responsiveness.

> With respect to the default behavior: Wouldn't a user/operator expect that the TLS drivers perform such online revocation check by default, if the CA/PKI is including those? E.g. if someone hosts a TLS rsyslog server with a public CA vendor, the server gets compromised the end-entity certificate of the server revoked by the CA. The OCSP server would know about the revoked certificate, the TLS rsyslog clients could then be "protected" talking to a compromised/revoked certificate. It just needs to be started in background and killed on shutdown.

(See snmp_start_trapreceiver  and snmp_stop_trapreceiver )

If you create sample ca / certifcates based on your script, but make them last longer (Like 36500 days) which is ok for the testbench, add them to here for example (tests/testsuites/x.509), you can use these tests as template to build your own test on: 

https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/sndrcv_tls_certvalid.sh

https://github.com/rsyslog/rsyslog/blob/master/tests/imtcp-tls-ossl-basic.sh

You can run single tests manually when you build rsyslog like this:
- go to rsyslog source dir
- export srcdir=./
- autoreconf -vfi 
- ./configure ... your options ...
- make && make check 
- ...wait until first tests runs then break with CTRL + C
- cd tests
- ./yourtestcase.sh

The whole document has a bit of a "POSIX-or-die" slant that might not be the most helpful, but in keeping with that motif, wouldn't it be more adaptive to set `--jobs "$(nproc)"` here rather than supply a fixed value when we have no a priori knowledge about their environment?

As far as the POSIX-or-die part, I think that can be resolved pretty well by prepending `bash -c` to what's already there (since we can reasonably assume that however someone got Git installed on Windows it includes a Bash interpreter in PATH) and replacing `~` with `$HOME` in the target path argument (PowerShell Core aliases that to $Env:UserProfile I'm pretty sure, no idea about CMD.exe though), but my familiarly with both the Windows Command Interpreter and Windows PowerShell makes me wish someone with more experience in that domain would spot check my thinking on that part.

This contribution raises interesting questions about the "Languages & Frameworks" section.

- Initially, the section was meant to indeed provide how-to guides for common languages and frameworks.
- When we had covered most languages, and started adding frameworks, it was confusing to mix frameworks with languages (e.g. a list like "C++, Ruby, Java, Pandas" doesn't make sense, because you're mixing languages and non-languages). So we decided to merge the frameworks into their specific language page (i.e. merge "Pandas" into the "Python" guide)
- However, the "Firebase" framework is not strongly related to one particular language, is it?

I still find it confusing to mix frameworks with languages, but we also can't merge Firebase into an existing language guide.

Maybe we should indeed have separate "Languages" and "Frameworks" sub-menus? Also, Firebase isn't even a "framework". Maybe it's more like a "tool", or "technology"? (Same goes for databases and such). So maybe let's have "Languages" and "Tools" sub-menus?

        if not args:

        y, z = args[0], args[1] if len(args) > 1 else ''
        if len(x) != len(y):

        tbl = dict(zip(x, y))

-0.9 - depending on FastAPI at the top of the stack to create smart objects makes sense but forcing it deep in managers completely bypasses all our abstractions and renders code that is meant to be useable outside the web server context only useful when coming from FastAPI. Transformations like this are inappropriate IMO.

This certainly can be reverted, but afaik `LibraryFolderDatabaseIdField` is not directly related to FastAPI, it is part of the schema module which managers already depend on. I thought the idea was to completely get rid of the manual encoding/decoding scattered across the entire code base and especially the managers and deal with it at the API layer so managers work always with simple integers.

But I agree this particular case was just a naive attempt to reduce manual handling of the `F` encoding for folders, but ideally, there will be no encoding at all here.

When indexes gets split by some uniform "property", like data origin, each index will contain same attribute (i.e. `data_origin`), and the value will be different for each index (`data_origin="Store"` or `data_origin="Blog"`), and same for all records across the index. In short: I don't have enough algolia experience to decide on this

Ok, I think it will be best to keep all the items — it will be just a generic way of accumulating categories, and the user will decide what should be done with it

@adehad @studioj Could you please take a look if this new pager meets the expectations? If so, I'd need some help to define how to test this as it will require a connection to a Jira server (similar to the resources tests) but the current ResultList is handled in test_client.py

@turran when writing this implementation do you have any thoughts on what would make a better user experience?

I have been wondering if we can have a look at options for breaking changes in a major version bump, and am considering if we can perhaps use httpx and move to true async support. 

But perhaps that would be a separate package. We've inherited a lot of baggage so might also be worth considering what a clean slate might gain.

@adehad Good point. IMHO when building a library you need to define where you put the criteria of what the library can do for the user and what not. So far, the current Jira Python bindings aim to mimic as much as possible the REST API and doing synchronous calls for that, at the HTTP level. There are plenty of situations where the current 1:1 python - REST API can be abstracted to give a better user experience, but that's not the current situation.

Still, the Jira REST API itself can be batched and already has asynchronous operations internally, like the UPM interface where you get a task id and then the user queries an specific endpoint with that task id to know the status of it. This can be abstracted on the python library again as a 1:1 with sync calls or put some logic above to do the task handling automatically for you, but that would require async code for sure and httpx seems like a good option there.

Now, for APIs that support batches, like searching issues by JQL, yielding them is enough and won't require much heavy change on the current code. At the end, the REST API that work with batches behaves like a generator already :) 



I think I'll need to see the ergonomics of this through an example to really make a call on whether this should exist as code in the library or maybe in the documentation as an example of optimizing / improving performance.

So if you still have some capacity to write a test that would be ideal. I would perhaps make a new `tests/test_paginator.py` and use an endpoint you deem suitable for the example.

As you say the `tests/resources/` is probably a good place to see the new tests structure. I think the `search_issues()` would be a good one to make an example for as that is where I can imagine most people trying to leverage this. You can try searching Atlassian's own Jira https://jira.atlassian.com/secure/Dashboard.jspa as they'll probably have much more tickets, and you won't need to authenticate to simply trawl through.


---- 

Thinking out loud

Maybe we can provide a `JiraAsync` class that uses a httpx session under the hood (vs a requests session) to start a process moving. A bit intimidating to look at all the functionality we support. But perhaps we can use the async class internally in the non-async class and simply have the non-async methods await the async methods. So users familiar with the sync calls could still benefit from async-ing the paginated endpoints for example.



----

Thanks again for taking the time for the PR and suggestions, hope we can figure out something that would work, and sorry that I'm a bit overly cautious for some changes !

I don't think we need an option for this; adding it doesn't break backwards-compatibiliity, and I don't imagine many users wanting to disable it. Here's some more info on how we typically approach options:

https://nacin.com/2011/12/18/in-open-source-learn-to-decide/
https://wordpress.org/about/philosophy/

It looks like the indentation is off a bit in a few places around this line.

The coding standards call for tabs instead of spaces.

We've got a custom `phpcs.xml.dist` file in Meta repo that describes the standards for WordCamp.org. Using `phpcs` makes it really easy to find any violations before committing. There's also a `.githooks/pre-commit` script in the Meta repo that you can use to automatically do PHP syntax checks, run `phpcs`, and run `phpmd` before committing. 

I'd recommend setting those up, even if you only run them manually. It's a lot easier than memorizing everything at first, and more consistent.

What do you think about using `npm` / `package.json` to register this as a dependency and include it, instead of manually bundling it?

That'd make it easier to get security notifications via `npm audit` and GitHub.

We'd still need to explicitly bundle it in the SVN repo, but that's no problem.

Kudos for doing coding standards fixes, and for doing them in a separate commit :)

The `Development Practices` doc has some helpful points on writing commit messages. 

> Use the imperative mood when possible: “Relax term ID comparisons…” instead of “Relaxes term ID comparisons…” [ from Core handbook ]

Something like `Replace spaces with tabs.`, or just a generic `Apply coding standards.` would fit a little bit better. 

This is one of the places we'd like to add it. It'd also be use it for the `currency` dropdown and the Summarize fields in wp-admin.

It's probably best to avoid updating the commit messages, rebasing, and force-pushing until we've finished reviewing everything else, though, since the force-push will wipe out a lot of the GitHub comments.

It sounds like one our coworkers has already [forked Select2 to make it accessible](https://github.com/woocommerce/selectwoo), so maybe we should switch to that instead?

If you feel like it, it might even be good to send a PR to selectWoo to merge in the upstream changes. That'd help us by fixing any bugs that haven't made it downstream; help selectWoo users for the same reason; and eventually help WP Core and Drupal, by making it easy to merge the a11y fixes upstream.

In general we try to be good open source citizens, but of course it always has to be balanced against time spent on our own priorities. This seems like a really good opportunity, though. 

Or, rather than trying to merge downstream, maybe it'd be better to just cherry-pick commits from downstream and send PRs upstream? That may be more efficient, since any changes will need to be tested in either direction. Whichever you think is best :)

We'll need to return task instances as dictionaries in our routes, so adding a helper method to do so will help us get rid of a lot of repetitive dictionary logic.

```
def to_dict(self):
    task = {
        "id": new_task.task_id,
        "title": new_task.title,
        "description": new_task.description,
        "is_complete": new_task.completed_at is not None

`queue.Queue` was created to work in concurrent environments spawned with the `threading` module, which is the behavior of the Azure exporters. With that being said, we probably shouldn't replace the default queue that is being used, since the original use case is supposed to be for the concurrent environments. I suggest adding the ability for the user to configure which type of queue they want by adding an option [here](https://github.com/census-instrumentation/opencensus-python/blob/master/contrib/opencensus-ext-azure/opencensus/ext/azure/common/__init__.py#L119). Then you can create a different type queue accordingly.

Why does object need to be serializable?

Please add an entry to the CHANGELOG

This doesn't work because `apply_telemetry_processors` is expecting an `Envelope` data type.

I think there are performance implications of doing this. We don't want to be mapping every time `logger.X()` is called.

In order to share messages/resources between different processes, the multiprocessing.Queue pickles the object so that it can be piped: https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/3.10/Lib/multiprocessing/queues.py#L244

It does work; the batch is a list of `Envelope` data type objects as I converted them already before putting them on the queue.

There is indeed a performance loss here. However it is not possible to put a raw `LogRecord` on the multiprocessing.Queue as it pickles the object.

It does work with threading, however in an environment where multiple processes are being used (see linked bug reports), the queue is not being shared between the different processes. Therefore a multiprocessing.Queue is required to get this to work.

column14:
I'm curious what prompted unwrapping these lines. Doing so exceeds the typical 80 column limit. Are you running a formatting tool?

👍 

One thing we can do to help our routes file from getting too large is to consider making multiple files containing routes separated by the resource type. We might have a `routes` folder instead of a `routes.py` file, and inside that folder (along with a `__init__.py`) we could have a file per resource, so `task.py` and `goal.py`. Where each would have a blueprint and endpoints for that resource. When we have one blueprint per file, we often name the blueprint simply `bp` rather  than including the resource name as part of it.

Then here, we could import and register the blueprints like
```python
    from .routes import task, goal
    app.register_blueprint(task.bp)
    app.register_blueprint(goal.bp)
```


According to the SqlAlchemy docs about [autoincrement](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/14/core/metadata.html#sqlalchemy.schema.Column.params.autoincrement):

> The default value is the string "auto" which indicates that a single-column primary key that is of an INTEGER type with no stated client-side or python-side defaults should receive auto increment semantics automatically; all other varieties of primary key columns will not.

This means that here, since the primary is not a compound key, the type is integer, and there's no specified default value, the desired autoincrement behavior will apply even without listing it. It doesn't hurt anything to list it, but it's not required.


Should we be able to create a goal with a NULL title? Consider adding `nullable=False` here.


👍 

Nice job having two different methods to provide the two different needed output styles. We could have used the `goal_dict` version to get the base values, then add in `tasks`, but given the size this seems ok.

Notice that as applications grow, we may end up with a large variety of endpoints that may need slightly different outputs. In that situation, rather than adding method after method to model class itself, we often will make helper _classes_ whose sole responsibility is knowing how to render a model instance into a certain output configuration. Sometimes we call these helper classes data transfer objects (DTOs).

It turns out that `nullable=True` is the default value for nullable. So all of the columns for Task here are currently marked as nullable. But should title or description be allowed to be NULL? (Does that make sense from a data standpoint?) Consider adding `nullable=False` to those columns.

The way the project emphasized that completed_at needs to accept NULL values may make it seem like we needed to explicitly call out that nullable should be True, but it turns out this is the default for nullable. Instead, we should think about the other data in our model and consider whether it makes sense for any of it to be NULL. If not, we can have the database help us protect against that happening!


Again, having these two methods is fine and clearly indicates to a caller that they might produce different output. But another approach would be to have a single dictionary function, and only add the `goal_id` field to the output if the task is associated with a goal. This means that the output format for the task could change depending on its data relationships, which could be confusing, but it also means that the task itself is the one deciding whether to include that information, which the argument could be made that the task is the best one to make that decision, rather than logic in a route. This would also allow this behavior to occur anywhere we return a task, whether individually or in a list.

Notice that, as written, getting multiple tasks would omit any goal information since the route wasn't updated to be aware of goals.

Unnecessary input, likely from a spurious autocomplete

No need to import the dotenv stuff anywhere but in the main `__init__.py` file. Once the settings have been loaded at startup, they become available in the `os.environ` without any further action.

Notice that the logic for GET and POST doesn't share any code, so if we wanted to try refactoring this we could consider putting the logic for each in separate functions, maybe `get_tasks` and `create_task`.

👍 

Good job enforcing the POST data requirements. We should be doing similar checks when PUTting a task as well. So we could also think about moving checks like this into validation helpers so that they are easier to reuse elsewhere.

We could even think about adding a class method to `Task` to create a new `Task` using the dictionary from a request body

```python
    @classmethod
    def from_dict(values):
        # create a new task, and set the model values from the values passed in
        # be sure to validate that all required values are present, we could return `None` or raise an error if needed
        return new_task
```


Also, nice use of `()` in the `if` to enable implicit line wrapping. This is prefered over using explicit line wrapping (`\` at the end of a line).

This can also be written as
```python
        tasks = Task.query.order_by(Task.title.asc())
```
which lets us avoid importing the `asc` function. We can do the same thing for `desc` and then that extra import could be removed.

Notice also that using the static column field `Task.title` has a greater opportunity for the IDE to correctly autocomplete, whereas using `"title"` could introduce typos.


👍 

Nice list comprehension!

Each of these verbs does depend on retrieving an existing task from the database by id, so there's a stronger case for keeping these together. But we could still think about splitting these into separate functions (e.g. `get_task`, `update_task`, and `delete_task`). We would need to either duplicate the lookup code in each function, or create a helper function that can be shared among the separated functions.


As alluded to earlier, should the route be the one that decides which model rendering function to use by inspecting the goal relationship within the task itself? Or should the task simply be asked to convert itself to a dictionary, and then it decides how to build the dictionary given its own internal state? It's not clear either way, but it's definitely worth thinking about!

We should be sure that the same fields required for POSTing are included here for PUT. PUT _replaces_ the value for the supplied task id, so we should ensure that all of the values required to represent a `Task` are provided with the same restrictions as we had when creating it in the first place.

At the least, we should ensure that the keys are present in the dictionary before trying to access them, otherwise this request would cause a `KeyError`.


Notice that this chunk of looking up an id, checking for None, and returning a 404 when not found recurs frequently. It's a little tricky to extract this into a helper function, mostly since a helper function can't force the calling function to exit. That is, unless it raises an error. So we could think about writing a helper function to perform this set of steps, but we would also need to customize the Flask error handling behavior to return JSON rather than HTML. There _is_ the `get_or_404` method that essentially does the lookup with errors already, but we would should still update the flask error handling (see [here](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/2.0.x/errorhandling/#error-handlers) for more details.)

Another approach could be to use a decorator to intercept the task id from the route, and performt the lookup before reaching the body of our endpoint. There's an example of that [here](https://github.com/AdaGold/hello-books-api-decorated/blob/main/app/routes.py).


Consider using `utcnow()` rather than `now()`, especially if there's no timezone information on the datetime in the database. When working with dates and time, it's usually a good idea to pass them around and store them in UTC, and only convert them to local time when needed for display (like in a UI). Working with dates and times is tricky!


👍 

Nice POST request to Slack!

Consider putting this part of the code into _its own_  helper function. All the mark complete endpoint really needs to know how to do is call a method that can post to Slack with the message to post. The rest of the details could be hidden in the helper, and potentially called from multiple places!


Similar feedback about splitting these functions, and moving validation and dictionary-handling logic around that I made for `Task` will also apply to `Goal`. These are common themes for any model with CRUD operations.


Good job checking whether the each requested task id lookup is successful before trying to append it to the task list. However, you may want to wait to perform the appending and commiting until after you have validated _all_ the tasks, rather than task by task. With the task-by-task approach, we could end up partially modifying the tasks in a goal, but then fail partway through the list, leaving the goal partially modified. It's often desirable to ensure that either the entire change has been applied, or none of the change has.

Appending to the tasks realtionship is absolutely a valid way to associate a task with a goal. Notice that it's not entirely clear from the project description or tests whether POSTing to the task list is _adding_ tasks to the goal (in addition to anything that was already there), or _replacing_ the tasks in the goal. Which perspective does your implementation take? How could we implement the other approach?


Don't forget to add a message to your migrations with `-m` when running the migration step.


We should remove the `pass` statement after supplying the test body.


An alternative to directly accessing the DB here would be to make an additional GET request. Doing so keeps us at the same level of abstraction (exercising the web API) while still checking that a change has been made (deletion of the goal) without assuming how the deletion is occuring (maybe we want to use a deleted flag rather than actually deleting the row).

There are two options to solve this:

1. Just return the response from the CS-API.
2. Return whatever the client is doing to provide the user list in their invite dialogs (and injecting them transparently into the results list without the widget noticing).

For 2., Element does many additional things that is currently implemented in the [`InviteDialog`](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-react-sdk/blob/e5291c195d3259b5905d72dc2945ed740fffc6d1/src/components/views/dialogs/InviteDialog.tsx). If we would want to provide the client-enhanced list instead of the raw server response, this would require refactoring in the react-sdk. But for the long term (if [MSC3008](https://github.com/matrix-org/matrix-spec-proposals/pull/3008) becomes a reality) it might be questionable how useful that would be. It could for example be an option to move the code to the js-sdk and expecting that future widgets will keep using that one. If the MSC is formulated openly enough, it could also leave other client authors the option to not do any additional processing here.

I agree with the thought, that the widget api should not be unnecassarly complex to implement for other clients. I think the better solution for a better user list would be to use the js-sdk for the widget and run the user list modifications to be done inside the widget.

I am wondering if using "we" is common in MSC's. I have not seen it before. I am not aware if there are any rules. But I think rephrasing without "we" would not hurt?

(this is very nitpicky indeed...)

Good point. I'm used to write ADRs for our own products which are written from our teams perspective. I will rewrite it later to better fit the MSC styling

This looks like it was copied from MSC2762 but doesn't quite fit here. Maybe the sentence "The widget is responsible..." should be removed completely?

Is this needed? Doesn't the following bullet point cover everything? (Or is this a standard sentence we include in this section?)

Not necessarily. So far, actions in the Widget API (like `read_event`, `send_event`, ...) are not prefixed with `m.*`, so the second point would not apply here. The first point mainly references the new permission `m.user_directory_search` while the second references the action `user_directory_search`.

This is is a copy from MSC2762 because it asks for the same behavior. MSC2762 is mainly defining the actions `read_event` and `send_event` but I would de-facto see it as a more general that kind-of defines the general behavior of the contract between the homeserver, the client, and the widget. But I'm fine with skipping it in this proposal.

column14:
So some initial feedback provided by @FSG-Cat & Nyaaori (not on Github) is that the MSC is still too focused on the sender local part and the concept of senders. As a result the proposal still leans towards / is coupled to current ideas about how to represent users and room members, and it is desirable to leave this open to interpretation at this point.

As a result, it has been suggested that an `origin` field be added to the top level of PDUs. Granted this is provided from the transactions endpoint, but while backfilling servers currently have to infer the origin from the `sender`.

I believe that it is possible to proxy this room version to clients without changing the client server api depending on how you implement users/members in a dependent MSC, even if sender is removed from the top level of PDUs. Still stands that it probably isn't desirable to emulate the existing behavior and it would just complicate things.

Neat helper function!

This section of code shows up in several other routes and is a great candidate for a helper function.  Returning a response from a helper function adds a little complexity, but using the Flask `abort` function could help there:
```
def get_task_fom_id(id):
    task = Task.query.get(id)
    if not task:
        abort(404)
    return task
```
The abort function will generate an HTML response by default, but passing `make_response` to abort makes it possible to send any type of response (ie, `abort(make_response("", 404))`).

Very thorough validation!  Nice work!

Great helper!

👍 

👍 

Interesting!  This query brings up some neat questions (what if there were other tasks in the db with a matching goal_id, or what if some of the task ids that were passed in aren't valid). 

This works well, but the db.relationship `tasks` in the Goal model does the query for you (note, I think as written now the db.relationship works this way, but please see my note in goal.py as there's a piece missing and I'm not sure how that effects it). In Goal, tasks will be set up as a list of Task models with the matching goal_id.
```suggestion
    goal = Goal.query.get(goal_id)
    if not goal:
        return "", 404
    tasks = [task.to_dict() for task in goal.tasks]
```

This db.relationship should generate a list of tasks (Task models) but it may need `back_populates` added:
```suggestion
    tasks = db.relationship('Task', back_populates="goal", lazy=True)
```
When using `back_populates` I think it's needed in the db.relationship on both ends (one & many).  However, using `backref` simplifies this:
```suggestion
    tasks = db.relationship('Task', backref="goal", lazy=True)
```
When using `backref`, the relationship on the other side is generated automatically, so line 12 of task.py can be removed.  Each Goal will have a `tasks` var that is a list of Task models, and each Task model will have a var `goal` that is the `Goal` model with the correct goal_id.

I can't comment on whether this PR makes sense, because I don't know and use Woopra. So, I focus on Python and documentation:

``` python
    woopra_settings = {
        'idle_timeout': 'WOOPRA_IDLE_TIMEOUT',

column14: Cette ligne ne doit pas être dans cette migration. Modifier le commentaire pour expliquer ce que fait cette migration; à la manière de https://github.com/n7consulting/Incipio/blob/master/src/Migrations/Version20190105082511.php#L11 Je vois plusieurs problèmes avec cette requête: 1. Naming: habituellement les fonctions findAllByX prennent X en argument. En regardant l'implémentation, cette requête devrait plutot s’appeler findAll 2. Problème de performance à venir avec cette fonction. Il faut utiliser une requête SQL au lieu de cette boucle (qui posera des problèmes dès que le nombre de contact se mettra à croître). 3. Problème de structure (ce qui explique 2). Cette fonction récupère tous les contacts puis les retourne groupés par alumnus. Tu peux obtenir exactement la même chose en faisant un select sur les alumnus qui ont plus d'un contact + un join sur ces contacts. Le résultat retourné sera exactement le même que cette requete mais évitera le point 2. Même remarques que pour `findAllByAlumnus` Le manager registry doit être récupéré depuis la classe, pas passé en paramètre. Exemple: https://github.com/n7consulting/Incipio/blob/master/src/Repository/Personne/MembreRepository.php#L31 Doit être fait via une requete SQL et non une boucle. Cette migration modifie des tables qui n'existent pas encore. Elle doit être supprimée pour ne pas créer d'erreurs comme https://github.com/n7consulting/Incipio/runs/4058979326?check_suite_focus=true#step:7:306 Corrigé via edit perso de la PR. Toutes les informations alumnis ne sont pas affichées lorsque l'on est sur la fiche d'un membre (URL: membres/voir/1). Ca réduit l'utilisabilité s'il faut aller éditer à chaque fois que l'on souhaite consulter les informations alumnis. De même, il faudrait afficher les contacts alumnis (n'afficher le cadre alumni que s'il y a des contacts ou des infos almunis) sur la fiche d'un membre. Erreur de copié-collé ? Mauvaise layout. Celle-ci est celle du suivi de projet Mauvaise layout. Celle-ci est celle du suivi de projet. Il faut rajouter les infos alumnis & alumnis contact à la partie RGPD. Plus de détails sur l'implémentation disponible ici: https://github.com/n7consulting/Incipio/pull/238/files En plus de modifier les templates pour inclure l'affichage des informations personnelles des alumnis, Il faut annoter les champs contenant des infos personnelles avec l'annotation `@Groups({"gdpr"})` pour qu'ils soient inclus dans l'export. L'ajout d'un bouton comme sur le pipeline de suivi d'étude n'est pas nécessaire (aucun action contextuelle supplémentaire) et rend l'affichage moins lisible (car moins de lignes par écran). Je partirais plutôt sur un simple lien vers la fiche de membre. pas de maxsize définie. Saisir un texte trop long génère une erreur 500. ``` An exception occurred while executing 'INSERT INTO AlumnusContact (date, objet, contenu, moyenContact, alumnus_id, faitPar_id) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)' with params ["2021-10-31 00:00:00", "g-gtg", "Un sous-r\u00e9seau est une subdivision logique d'un r\u00e9seau de taille plus importante. Un sous-r\u00e9seau correspond typiquement \u00e0 un r\u00e9seau local sous-jacent.", "Mail", 2, 1]: SQLSTATE[22001]: String data, right truncated: 1406 Data too long for column 'contenu' at row 1 ``` 255 pour un titre est assez long. 128 devrait suffire. Le champ est marqué nullable alors qu'il est required dans le formulaire. Autant ne pas le marquer comme nullable Contenu est trop court. 255 caractères me semble très limité Pareil qu'objet. Le champ n'a pas besoin d'etre nullable s'il est required dans le formulaire. /!\ Attention aux migrations en cas d'édition Pas besoin d'etre nullable. Pas besoin d'etre si long quand les options proposées sont 'mail', 'telephone', 'physique', 'lettre'. Au passage sur les moyens de contacts, vous pourriez peut être ajouté 'réseaux sociaux' pour couvrir les contacts via Linkedin Cette classe n'est pas importée. Concernant les FormHandler, faire une classe à part entière pour finalement si peu de validation et ne l'utiliser qu'à un endroit est discutable. (le ratio complexité / bénéfices me semble limité). Le code commenté doit être supprimé Ca serait pratique d'avoir un lien vers la liste des contacts dans le breadcrumb Ne pas afficher le lien si le champ est vide: ```suggestion {% if alumnus.alumnus.lienLinkedIn %} {{ 'rh.voir_profil'|trans({}, 'rh') }} {% endif %} ``` C'est un détail, mais sémantiquement plus correct. Il y a un bug dans la gestion des alumnis. Voici comment le reproduire. 1. Ouvrir le profil d'un membre sans profil alumni. 2. Modifier l'email 3. Enregistrer => Le membre apparaît dans la liste des alumnis alors qu'aucune information alumni n'est renseignée. A priori, un membre ne devrait apparaitre dans la liste des alumnis que si des informations alumnis sont renseignées. Une meilleur option serait de ne pas créer l'entité alumni si tous les champs sont nuls. Et de garder l'ancienne requete. Commentaire ne doit pas être annoté `gdpr`. Sinon il se retrouvera dans l'export d'une personne. Et d'expérience, le contenu des commentaires est parfois très honnête; pas quelque chose que l'on veut partager. Enfin commentaire ne contient pas d'infos appartenant à la personne. Donc l’anonymiser est parfait. mais l'exporter ne l'est pas. Is it normal that on the `access.html.twig` template I can access non-gdpr attributes from `alumnus` class ?

This would be more in keeping with the previous code:
```suggestion
            return any('learning.oreilly.com/%s/' % x in urlh.geturl() for x in ('member/login', 'home'))
```

Depending on how oreilly is accessed, the URL can end up being "https://learning.oreilly.com/member/login/?next=[snip]" for cases where the user is not yet logged in.  So we don't want to catch that case here with the `in` instead of `==`.

Given that, is there a more conventional way to format the check being done here?



Maybe 
```sugg
            return bool(re.search(r'learning.oreilly.com/(?:%s)' % '|'.join(('member/login/$', 'home/')), urlh.geturl()))
```
or 
```sugg
            parsed_url = compat_urlparse.urlparse(url)
            return parsed_url.hostname.endswith('learning.oreilly.com') and (
                parsed_url.path.startswith('/home/')
                or (parsed_url.path == '/member/login' and not parsed_url.query))
```
Pick either of these or your original, check your test, and then I think it's good to go.

```suggestion
As the level increases so does that individual's responsibility accordingly. 
```

```suggestion
The MoE seeks out opportunities for contributors to move up the scale if they are happy to do so, and the community manager will ensure this happens and opportunities are available. 
```

```suggestion
When new members show interest in being a part of the project, they will be onboarded and briefed on the project's aims and objectives as well as progress updates. 
```

```suggestion
This will be in the form of an onboarding pack which includes all materials that are needed to succesfully understand the project, as well as a 1:1 chat with the Community Manager who will ensure all information is understood. 
```

Is the 1:1 chat something we can offer as the project grows? If you have capacity to do this, that's great! The strategy can also be changed if needed.

Fab!

It will also be a space in which individuals can come together and work in collaboaration on different topics and provide support wherever needed. 
```

It includes project updates as well as any information, resources or opportunities associated with AutSPACEs. 
```

column14:
What about https support? Regex expression allows https, but `$domain =` forgets that.

 Btw., is this an old (separate) issue, which always existed (eventually add a new/separate github issue?)?

Well, we have to make some assumptions. If the passed domain has a scheme, everything is ok, so no scheme is prepended. If there is no scheme - so the regex doesn't match - I think we can't reliably guess the correct scheme at this code line (because in fact, the domain could be any domain, which could have https support or not), so the best is to stick with http ;-)

Instead of the regex a parse_url call could be used to check, if there is a scheme. Or we could make the regex more general (`'/[a-z]+:\/\//i'`).

If the user of this method really wants to specify the scheme, it could be done with the `$domain` parameter. Maybe it's more clear to rename the parameter from `$domain` to something like `$baseUrlOverride`

This is not the place to add this. This script file is the admin base, it means it will be run on any page. You must only do some script for that SendEmail action view. Check my idea of how doing that: https://github.com/shuup/shuup/compare/master...chessbr:send-email-custom-script?expand=1 Basically you inject a template for SendEmail action at the end of the other scripts.

Also, instead or relying on `DOMSubtreeModified` event, you probably just need to setup a time interval `setInterval()` to update the preview each 2-3 seconds when the preview is visible and remove it when the preview is closed.

Example: https://codemirror.net/demo/preview.html

I am not sure ALL actions will have this preview feature, basically just `SendEmail`. Add an attribute called `supports_preview = False` in base `Action` class (shuup/notify/base.py) and set it to True in `SendMail` action. Once that is set, you probably can use it to check whether to add a preview here or not.

column14:
Mandatory, not mendatory

It was necessary for my application as we have to authenticate users with a JWT token without a JTI claim. We don't own the JWT creation which is done by another external service and JWT comes without JTI claim.
We use django-rest-framework-simplejwt only to verify token with the private key (this is the important part of the authentication for me, not the jti ) and receive an authenticated user. 
We don't use the token creation part.
A more precise name for the option would be:
`ALLOW_THIRD_PARTY_TOKEN_WITHOUT_JTI_CLAIM : True`
